{"title_page": "Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on domestic violence", "text_new": "Amid the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] many countries have reported an increase in domestic violence. [[United Nations]] Secretary-General [[Ant\u00f3nio Guterres]], noting the \"horrifying global surge\" has called for a domestic violence \"ceasefire\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/04/1061052|title=UN chief calls for domestic violence \u2018ceasefire\u2019 amid \u2018horrifying global surge\u2019|date=2020-04-05|website=UN News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/domestic-violence-rises-amid-coronavirus-lockdowns-in-asia/a-53077378|title=Domestic violence rises amid coronavirus lockdowns in Asia|last=Godbole|first=Tanika|date=9 April 2020|website=Deutsche Welle (DW)|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> France, in the first week of its lockdown saw a 30 percent rise in domestic violence cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200410-french-domestic-violence-cases-soar-during-coronavirus-lockdown|title=French domestic violence cases soar during coronavirus lockdown|date=2020-04-10|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> France's [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior]] announced that said there had been a 36% increase in police intervention for domestic violence cases in Paris after the lockdown measures were enacted.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/europe/domestic-violence-coronavirus-lockdown-intl/index.html|title=Women are using code words at pharmacies to escape domestic violence|last=Kottasov\u00e1|first=Ivana|last2=Donato|first2=Valentina Di|date=6 April 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> [[Refuge (United Kingdom charity)|Refuge]], a [[United Kingdom]] charity concerned with domestic violence, said on 6 April 2020 that calls to its helpline had risen by 25% since restrictions began and that hits on its website had increased by 150%.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Australian government said that Google has registered the most searches for domestic violence help in the past five years during the outbreak.<ref name=\":0\" /> India's [[National Commission for Women]] has seen a more than twofold rise in gender-based violence during the lockdown in India; total complaints from women rose from 116 in the first week of March to 257 in the final week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/india-news-rise-in-domestic-violence-across-all-strata-of-society-in-the-coronavirus-lockdown-period/350249|title=Domestic Violence Cases Across India Swell Since Coronavirus Lockdown|last=Roy|first=Lachmi Deb|date=7 April 2020|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nWhile reporting their abuse, 951 callers between 10 and 24 March mentioned Covid-19, on the [[National Domestic Violence Hotline]]. One caller to the hotline said that she was being \"she was being kept home against her will after being threatened by her abuser with a hammer and an unregistered gun\" who was using the pandemic as an excuse to stop her from leaving home.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Fielding|first=Sarah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/03/coronavirus-quarantine-abuse-domestic-violence|title=In quarantine with an abuser: surge in domestic violence reports linked to coronavirus|date=2020-04-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn Italy, there has been a steep fall in calls to domestic violence helplines. Another support group in France has seen the same trend of drop in calls. This may be attributed to women finding it difficult to ask from help during the confinement of a lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reuters|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/04/world/europe/04reuters-health-coronavirus-italy-violence.html|title=In Italy, Support Groups Fear Lockdown Is Silencing Domestic Abuse Victims|date=2020-04-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As TIME magazine reports that the, \"mandatory lockdowns [...] have trapped them in their homes with their abusers, isolated from the people and the resources that could help them\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5803887/coronavirus-domestic-violence-victims/|title=How Coronavirus Is Affecting Victims of Domestic Violence|last=Godin|first=Melissa|date=18 March 2020|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nGovernments have come up with new ways to tackle domestic violence in the times of restriction imposed due to lockdowns during the coronavirus pandemic. Italy has launched an app that allows asking for help without the need to make a phone call. France has roped in pharmacies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/european-countries-develop-new-ways-tackle-domestic-violence-during-coronavirus-n1174301|title=European countries develop new ways to tackle domestic violence during lockdowns|last=Talmazan|first=Yuliya|last2=Sirna|first2=Lidia|date=3 April 2020|website=NBC News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11|last3=Ratto|first3=Hernan Mu\u00f1oz|last4=Ing|first4=Nancy}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "Amid the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] many countries have reported an increase in domestic violence. [[United Nations]] Secretary-General [[Ant\u00f3nio Guterres]], noting the \"horrifying global surge\" has called for a domestic violence \"ceasefire\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/04/1061052|title=UN chief calls for domestic violence \u2018ceasefire\u2019 amid \u2018horrifying global surge\u2019|date=2020-04-05|website=UN News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/domestic-violence-rises-amid-coronavirus-lockdowns-in-asia/a-53077378|title=Domestic violence rises amid coronavirus lockdowns in Asia|last=Godbole|first=Tanika|date=9 April 2020|website=Deutsche Welle (DW)|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> France, in the first week of its lockdown saw a 30 percent rise in domestic violence cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200410-french-domestic-violence-cases-soar-during-coronavirus-lockdown|title=French domestic violence cases soar during coronavirus lockdown|date=2020-04-10|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> France's [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior]] announced that said there had been a 36% increase in police intervention for domestic violence cases in Paris after the lockdown measures were enacted.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/europe/domestic-violence-coronavirus-lockdown-intl/index.html|title=Women are using code words at pharmacies to escape domestic violence|last=Kottasov\u00e1|first=Ivana|last2=Donato|first2=Valentina Di|date=6 April 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> [[Refuge (United Kingdom charity)|Refuge]], a [[United Kingdom]] charity concerned with domestic violence, said on 6 April 2020 that calls to its helpline had risen by 25% since restrictions began and that hits on its website had increased by 150%.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Australian government said that Google has registered the most searches for domestic violence help in the past five years during the outbreak.<ref name=\":0\" /> India's [[National Commission for Women]] has seen a more than twofold rise in gender-based violence during the lockdown in India; total complaints from women rose from 116 in the first week of March to 257 in the final week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/india-news-rise-in-domestic-violence-across-all-strata-of-society-in-the-coronavirus-lockdown-period/350249|title=Domestic Violence Cases Across India Swell Since Coronavirus Lockdown|last=Roy|first=Lachmi Deb|date=7 April 2020|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nWhile reporting their abuse, 951 callers between 10 and 24 March mentioned Covid-19, on the [[National Domestic Violence Hotline]]. One caller to the hotline said that she was being \"she was being kept home against her will after being threatened by her abuser with a hammer and an unregistered gun\" who was using the pandemic as an excuse to stop her from leaving home.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Fielding|first=Sarah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/03/coronavirus-quarantine-abuse-domestic-violence|title=In quarantine with an abuser: surge in domestic violence reports linked to coronavirus|date=2020-04-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn Italy, there has been a steep fall in calls to domestic violence helplines. Another support group in France has seen the same trend of drop in calls. This may be attributed to women finding it difficult to ask from help during the confinement of a lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reuters|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/04/world/europe/04reuters-health-coronavirus-italy-violence.html|title=In Italy, Support Groups Fear Lockdown Is Silencing Domestic Abuse Victims|date=2020-04-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As TIME magazine reports that the, \"mandatory lockdowns [...] have trapped them in their homes with their abusers, isolated from the people and the resources that could help them\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5803887/coronavirus-domestic-violence-victims/|title=How Coronavirus Is Affecting Victims of Domestic Violence|last=Godin|first=Melissa|date=18 March 2020|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nGovernments have come up with new ways to tackle domestic violence in the times of restriction imposed due to lockdowns during the coronavirus pandemic. Italy has launched a app that allows asking for help without the need to make a phone call. France has roped in pharmacies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/european-countries-develop-new-ways-tackle-domestic-violence-during-coronavirus-n1174301|title=European countries develop new ways to tackle domestic violence during lockdowns|last=Talmazan|first=Yuliya|last2=Sirna|first2=Lidia|date=3 April 2020|website=NBC News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11|last3=Ratto|first3=Hernan Mu\u00f1oz|last4=Ing|first4=Nancy}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: a app \u2192 an app", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_domestic_violence"}
{"title_page": "Black bulbul", "text_new": "{{For|the south-eastern Indian Ocean species using the same name|Malagasy bulbul}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{Cite iucn | author = BirdLife International | title = ''Hypsipetes leucocephalus'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T103823996A94366953 | date = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103823996A94366953.en}}</ref>\n| image = Black Bulbul I IMG 6662.jpg\n| image_caption = ''H. l. psaroides''\n| taxon = Hypsipetes leucocephalus\n| authority = ([[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|Gmelin]], 1789)\n| range_map = \n| range_map_caption = \n| synonyms = * ''Turdus leucocephalus'' <small>[[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|Gmelin]], 1789</small>\n* ''Hypsipetes madagascariensis''\n* ''Hypsipetes madagascariensis leucocephalus''\n* ''Microscelis leucocephalus''\n}}\n\nThe '''black bulbul''' (''Hypsipetes leucocephalus''), also known as the '''Himalayan black bulbul''' or '''Asian black bulbul''', is a member of the [[bulbul]] family of [[passerine]] [[bird]]s. It is found in southern Asia from  India east to southern China. It is the [[type species]] of the [[genus]] ''[[Hypsipetes]]'', established by [[Nicholas Aylward Vigors]] in the early 1830s.<ref name=gregory2000/> There are a number of [[subspecies]], mostly varying in the shade of the body plumage which ranges from grey to black, and some also occur in white-headed [[Morph (zoology)|morphs]], as also suggested by its [[specific name (zoology)|specific epithet]] ''leucocephalus'', literally \"white head\". The legs and bill are always rich orange-red.\n\n==Taxonomy and systematics==\n[[File:HypsipetesLeucocephalusTailFBI.jpg|thumb|left|The tail of ''H. l. psaroides'' has a gentle curve in the outer tail feathers and a shallow fork]]\nThe black bulbul was originally described in the genus [[Turdus]] and has also been considered as either [[conspecific]] with or as subspecies of the [[Malagasy bulbul]].<ref name = Warren/> The common name 'black bulbul' is also used as an alternate name by the Malagasy bulbul. Formerly, the [[square-tailed bulbul]] was also classified as two subspecies of the black bulbul.\n\n=== Subspecies ===\nTen subspecies are currently recognized, although the reproductive isolation mechanisms such as [[bird vocalization|vocalization]] and geographic distributions of these populations still remain to be studied:<ref name=dickinson/><ref name=\"ioc\"/>\n\n* ''H. l. psaroides'' - <small>[[Nicholas Aylward Vigors|Vigors]], 1831</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found along the Himalayas from the Kunar Valley (north-eastern Afghanistan) and northern Pakistan through Arunachal Pradesh (northern India) and the central Himalayas to north-western Myanmar\n* '''Assam black bulbul''' (''H. l. nigrescens'') - <small>[[E. C. Stuart Baker|Baker, ECS]], 1917</small>: Found in [[Assam]] and [[Manipur]] (north-eastern India), and the [[Chin Hills]] (western Myanmar)\n* '''Burmese black bulbul''' (''H. l. concolor'') - <small>[[Edward Blyth|Blyth]], 1849</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found from eastern Myanmar and southern [[Yunnan]] (southern China) through Indochina\n* ''H. l. ambiens'' - <small>([[Ernst Mayr|Mayr]], 1942)</small>: Found in north-eastern Myanmar and western Yunnan (southern China)\n* ''H. l. sinensis'' - <small>([[John David Digues La Touche|La Touche]], 1922)</small>: Found in northern Yunnan (southern China)\n* ''H. l. stresemanni'' - <small>(Mayr, 1942)</small>: Members of this race have white heads. Found in central Yunnan (southern China)\n* ''H. l. leucothorax'' - <small>(Mayr, 1942)</small>: Members of this race have white heads. Found in central China\n* ''H. l. leucocephalus'' - <small>([[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|Gmelin, JF]], 1789)</small>: Members of this race have white heads. Found in south-eastern China\n* ''H. l. nigerrimus'' - <small>([[John Gould|Gould]], 1863)</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found in Taiwan\n* ''H. l. perniger'' - <small>[[Robert Swinhoe|R. Swinhoe]], 1870</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found on Hainan (off south-eastern China)\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Hypsipetes leucocephalus -Prague Zoo-8a-3c.jpg|thumb|White-headed morph of the nominate race]]\n[[File:Hypsipetes leucocephalus P5154241.jpg|thumb|Individual at [[Taipei Botanical Garden|Botanical Garden]] in the city of [[Taipei]]]]\n[[File:Black Bulbul.jpg|thumb|Black bulbul (''Hypsipetes leucocephalus psaroides'') [[Himachal Pradesh]], India]]\nThe black bulbul is {{convert|24|\u2013|25|cm|abbr=on}} in length, with a long tail. The body plumage ranges from slate grey to shimmering black, depending on the race. The beak, legs, and feet are all orange and the head has a black fluffy crest. Sexes are similar in plumage, but young birds lack the crest, have whitish underparts with a grey breast band, and have a brown tint to the upperparts. They have a black streak behind the eye and on the ear coverts.<ref name=hbk/><ref name=fbi/><ref name=fbi2/>\n\n===Vocalisations===\nThey can be quite noisy, making various loud cheeping, mewing and grating calls.<ref name=hbk/> The Himalayan form has been reported to make a call resembling a goat kid, throwing back its neck when calling.<ref name=Page/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThis bulbul is found in broad-leaved forests, cultivation and gardens mainly in hilly areas, but Himalayan populations are known to sometimes descend into the adjoining plains in winter.<ref name=\"pcr\"/><ref name=raza/><ref name=gaston/>\n\n===Breeding===\nIt builds its nest in a tree or bush; the nest is a cup placed in a fork and made from grasses, dry leaves, mosses, lichens and cobwebs. The lining is made up of ferns, rootlets and other soft material.<ref name=hume/> Both sexes participate in nest construction.  Two or three eggs form the usual clutch.\n\n===Food and feeding===\nBlack bulbuls feed mainly on seeds and insects, and they are often seen in small groups, either roosting or flying about in search of food. They are particularly fond of berries. They are known to feed on a wide range of berries including ''Celtis'', ''Rosa'', ''Melia'' and ''Ehretia'' in the Himalayas.<ref name=narang/> They feed on the nectar of ''Salmalia'', ''Erythrina'', ''Rhododendron'' and other species. They make [[Hawking (birds)|aerial sallies]] for insects.<ref name=pcr/>\n[[File:Hypsipetes leucocephalus (All).jpg|thumb|Black bulbul]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist |refs =\n<ref name=dickinson>{{cite journal|author1=Dickinson, E.C.|author2=R.W.R.J. Dekker|author3=S. Eck|author4=S. Somadikarta|year=2002|title=Systematic notes on Asian birds. 26. Types of the Pycnonotidae|url=http://www.naturalis.nl/sites/naturalis.en/contents/i000308/snab026.pdf|url-status=dead|journal=Zool. Verh. Leiden|volume=340|pages=115\u2013160|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025005104/http://www.naturalis.nl//sites/naturalis.en/contents/i000308/snab026.pdf|archivedate=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=fbi>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/birdsindia01oaterich#page/260/mode/1up/|pages=259\u2013263|author=Blanford WT|year=1889|publisher=Taylor and Francis, London |title= The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma: Birds Volume 1}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=fbi2>{{cite book|pages=368\u2013373 |title= The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Birds|volume=1| edition=2nd| author=Baker, ECS|url=https://archive.org/stream/faunaofbritishin01bake#page/369/mode/1up/ |publisher=Taylor and Francis, London| year=1924}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=gaston>{{cite journal|author= Gaston, AJ |year=1972| title=Black Bulbuls ''Hypsipetes madagascariensis'' (P.L.S. Muller) in Delhi|journal= Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=69|issue=3|pages=651\u2013652|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48289642}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=gregory2000>{{cite journal| author=Gregory, Steven M.| year=2000| title=Nomenclature of the '''Hypsipetes''' Bulbuls (Pycnonotidae)| journal=Forktail| volume=16| pages=164\u2013166| url=http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/16pdfs/Gregory-Bulbuls.pdf| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828051747/http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/16pdfs/Gregory-Bulbuls.pdf| archivedate=2008-08-28}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=hbk>{{cite book|author1=Ali, S |author2=S D Ripley |lastauthoramp=yes | title=Handbook of the birds of India and Pakistan|edition=2nd|publisher=Oxford University Press|volume= 6|year= 1996 |pages =109\u2013113}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=hume>{{cite book|url= https://archive.org/stream/nestseggsofindia01humerich#page/164/mode/1up/| pages=164\u2013168|year=1889|title=The nests and eggs of Indian birds|author=Hume, A.O.|edition=2nd| volume=1|publisher=R H Porter, London}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ioc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/bulbuls/|title=Bulbuls|year=2017|editor1-last=Gill|editor1-first=Frank|editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist)|editor2-last=Donsker|editor2-first=David|work=World Bird List Version 7.3|publisher=International Ornithologists' Union|accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=narang>{{cite journal|author1=Narang, ML |author2=Rana, RS |year=1999| title= Black Bulbuls association with ''Melia azedarach''|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] |volume=38| issue=6| page=104| url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW38_6#page/n15/mode/1up/}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Page>{{cite journal|title=The Himalayan Black Bulbul. ''Hypsipetes psaroides''|author=Page, WT|pages=209\u2013211| url=https://archive.org/stream/aviculturalmagaz01avic#page/209/mode/1up|journal=Avicultural Magazine|volume=1|issue=6|year=1903}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"pcr\">{{cite book |title=Birds of South Asia. The Ripley Guide. Volume 2|author1=Rasmussen PC|author2=JC Anderton|publisher=Smithsonian Institution & Lynx Edicions|year=2005|pages=342\u2013344|lastauthoramp=yes}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=raza>{{cite journal|author=Raza, RH |year=1993| title= Sighting of Black Bulbul ''Hypsipetes madagascariensis'' (P.L.S. Muller) in Gaya, Bihar| journal= ''Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society'' |volume=90|issue=2|page= 291|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48609546}}</ref>\n\n<ref name = Warren>Warren BH, Bermingham E, RP Prys-Jones & C Thebaud (2005) Tracking island colonization history and phenotypic shifts in Indian Ocean bulbuls (''Hypsipetes'': Pycnonotidae). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 85:271\u2013287 [http://stri.si.edu/bermingham/Publications/papers/biff_papers/EB,%20Avian%20Bulbuls%20BJLS%202005.pdf PDF]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q998240}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:bulbul, black}}\n[[Category:Hypsipetes|black bulbul]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Himalayas]]\n[[Category:Birds of Eastern Himalaya]]\n[[Category:Birds of China]]\n[[Category:Birds of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Birds of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Birds of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1789|black bulbul]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the south-eastern Indian Ocean species using the same name|Malagasy bulbul}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{Cite iucn | author = BirdLife International | title = ''Hypsipetes leucocephalus'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T103823996A94366953 | date = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103823996A94366953.en}}</ref>\n| image = Black Bulbul I IMG 6662.jpg\n| image_caption = ''H. l. psaroides''\n| taxon = Hypsipetes leucocephalus\n| authority = ([[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|Gmelin]], 1789)\n| range_map = \n| range_map_caption = \n| synonyms = * ''Turdus leucocephalus'' <small>[[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|Gmelin]], 1789</small>\n* ''Hypsipetes madagascariensis''\n* ''Hypsipetes madagascariensis leucocephalus''\n* ''Microscelis leucocephalus''\n}}\n\nThe '''black bulbul''' (''Hypsipetes leucocephalus''), also known as the '''Himalayan black bulbul''' or '''Asian black bulbul''', is a member of the [[bulbul]] family of [[passerine]] [[bird]]s. It is found in southern Asia from  India east to southern China. It is the [[type species]] of the [[genus]] ''[[Hypsipetes]]'', established by [[Nicholas Aylward Vigors]] in the early 1830s.<ref name=gregory2000/> There are a number of [[subspecies]], mostly varying in the shade of the body plumage which ranges from grey to black, and some also occur in white-headed [[Morph (zoology)|morphs]], as also suggested by its [[specific name (zoology)|specific epithet]] ''leucocephalus'', literally \"white head\". The legs and bill are always rich orange-red.\n\n==Taxonomy and systematics==\n[[File:HypsipetesLeucocephalusTailFBI.jpg|thumb|left|The tail of ''H. l. psaroides'' has a gentle curve in the outer tail feathers and a shallow fork]]\nThe black bulbul was originally described in the genus [[Turdus]] and has also been considered as either [[conspecific]] with or as subspecies of the [[Malagasy bulbul]].<ref name = Warren/> The common name 'black bulbul' is also used as an alternate name by the Malagasy bulbul. Formerly, the [[square-tailed bulbul]] was also classified as two subspecies of the black bulbul.\n\n=== Subspecies ===\nTen subspecies are currently recognized, although the reproductive isolation mechanisms such as [[bird vocalization|vocalization]] and geographic distributions of these populations still remain to be studied:<ref name=dickinson/><ref name=\"ioc\"/>\n\n* ''H. l. psaroides'' - <small>[[Nicholas Aylward Vigors|Vigors]], 1831</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found along the Himalayas from the Kunar Valley (north-eastern Afghanistan) and northern Pakistan through Arunachal Pradesh (northern India) and the central Himalayas to north-western Myanmar\n* '''Assam black bulbul''' (''H. l. nigrescens'') - <small>[[E. C. Stuart Baker|Baker, ECS]], 1917</small>: Found in [[Assam]] and [[Manipur]] (north-eastern India), and the [[Chin Hills]] (western Myanmar)\n* '''Burmese black bulbul''' (''H. l. concolor'') - <small>[[Edward Blyth|Blyth]], 1849</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found from eastern Myanmar and southern [[Yunnan]] (southern China) through Indochina\n* ''H. l. ambiens'' - <small>([[Ernst Mayr|Mayr]], 1942)</small>: Found in north-eastern Myanmar and western Yunnan (southern China)\n* ''H. l. sinensis'' - <small>([[John David Digues La Touche|La Touche]], 1922)</small>: Found in northern Yunnan (southern China)\n* ''H. l. stresemanni'' - <small>(Mayr, 1942)</small>: Members of this race have white heads. Found in central Yunnan (southern China)\n* ''H. l. leucothorax'' - <small>(Mayr, 1942)</small>: Members of this race have white heads. Found in central China\n* ''H. l. leucocephalus'' - <small>([[Johann Friedrich Gmelin|Gmelin, JF]], 1789)</small>: Members of this race have white heads. Found in south-eastern China\n* ''H. l. nigerrimus'' - <small>([[John Gould|Gould]], 1863)</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found in Taiwan\n* ''H. l. perniger'' - <small>[[Robert Swinhoe|R. Swinhoe]], 1870</small>: Originally described as a separate species. Found on Hainan (off south-eastern China)\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Hypsipetes leucocephalus -Prague Zoo-8a-3c.jpg|thumb|White-headed morph of the nominate race]]\n[[File:Hypsipetes leucocephalus P5154241.jpg|thumb|Individual at [[Taipei Botanical Garden|Botanical Garden]] in the city of [[Taipei]]]]\n[[File:Black Bulbul.jpg|thumb|Black bulbul (''Hypsipetes leucocephalus psaroides'') [[Himachal Pradesh]], India]]\nThe black bulbul is {{convert|24|\u2013|25|cm|abbr=yes}} in length, with a long tail. The body plumage ranges from slate grey to shimmering black, depending on the race. The beak, legs, and feet are all orange and the head has a black fluffy crest. Sexes are similar in plumage, but young birds lack the crest, have whitish underparts with a grey breast band, and have a brown tint to the upperparts. They have a black streak behind the eye and on the ear coverts.<ref name=hbk/><ref name=fbi/><ref name=fbi2/>\n\n===Vocalisations===\nThey can be quite noisy, making various loud cheeping, mewing and grating calls.<ref name=hbk/> The Himalayan form has been reported to make a call resembling a goat kid, throwing back its neck when calling.<ref name=Page/>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThis bulbul is found in broad-leaved forests, cultivation and gardens mainly in hilly areas, but Himalayan populations are known to sometimes descend into the adjoining plains in winter.<ref name=\"pcr\"/><ref name=raza/><ref name=gaston/>\n\n===Breeding===\nIt builds its nest in a tree or bush; the nest is a cup placed in a fork and made from grasses, dry leaves, mosses, lichens and cobwebs. The lining is made up of ferns, rootlets and other soft material.<ref name=hume/> Both sexes participate in nest construction.  Two or three eggs form the usual clutch.\n\n===Food and feeding===\nBlack bulbuls feed mainly on seeds and insects, and they are often seen in small groups, either roosting or flying about in search of food. They are particularly fond of berries. They are known to feed on a wide range of berries including ''Celtis'', ''Rosa'', ''Melia'' and ''Ehretia'' in the Himalayas.<ref name=narang/> They feed on the nectar of ''Salmalia'', ''Erythrina'', ''Rhododendron'' and other species. They make [[Hawking (birds)|aerial sallies]] for insects.<ref name=pcr/>\n[[File:Hypsipetes leucocephalus (All).jpg|thumb|Black bulbul]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist |refs =\n<ref name=dickinson>{{cite journal|author1=Dickinson, E.C.|author2=R.W.R.J. Dekker|author3=S. Eck|author4=S. Somadikarta|year=2002|title=Systematic notes on Asian birds. 26. Types of the Pycnonotidae|url=http://www.naturalis.nl/sites/naturalis.en/contents/i000308/snab026.pdf|url-status=dead|journal=Zool. Verh. Leiden|volume=340|pages=115\u2013160|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025005104/http://www.naturalis.nl//sites/naturalis.en/contents/i000308/snab026.pdf|archivedate=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=fbi>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/birdsindia01oaterich#page/260/mode/1up/|pages=259\u2013263|author=Blanford WT|year=1889|publisher=Taylor and Francis, London |title= The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma: Birds Volume 1}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=fbi2>{{cite book|pages=368\u2013373 |title= The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Birds|volume=1| edition=2nd| author=Baker, ECS|url=https://archive.org/stream/faunaofbritishin01bake#page/369/mode/1up/ |publisher=Taylor and Francis, London| year=1924}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=gaston>{{cite journal|author= Gaston, AJ |year=1972| title=Black Bulbuls ''Hypsipetes madagascariensis'' (P.L.S. Muller) in Delhi|journal= Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=69|issue=3|pages=651\u2013652|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48289642}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=gregory2000>{{cite journal| author=Gregory, Steven M.| year=2000| title=Nomenclature of the '''Hypsipetes''' Bulbuls (Pycnonotidae)| journal=Forktail| volume=16| pages=164\u2013166| url=http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/16pdfs/Gregory-Bulbuls.pdf| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828051747/http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/16pdfs/Gregory-Bulbuls.pdf| archivedate=2008-08-28}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=hbk>{{cite book|author1=Ali, S |author2=S D Ripley |lastauthoramp=yes | title=Handbook of the birds of India and Pakistan|edition=2nd|publisher=Oxford University Press|volume= 6|year= 1996 |pages =109\u2013113}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=hume>{{cite book|url= https://archive.org/stream/nestseggsofindia01humerich#page/164/mode/1up/| pages=164\u2013168|year=1889|title=The nests and eggs of Indian birds|author=Hume, A.O.|edition=2nd| volume=1|publisher=R H Porter, London}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ioc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/bulbuls/|title=Bulbuls|year=2017|editor1-last=Gill|editor1-first=Frank|editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist)|editor2-last=Donsker|editor2-first=David|work=World Bird List Version 7.3|publisher=International Ornithologists' Union|accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=narang>{{cite journal|author1=Narang, ML |author2=Rana, RS |year=1999| title= Black Bulbuls association with ''Melia azedarach''|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] |volume=38| issue=6| page=104| url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW38_6#page/n15/mode/1up/}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Page>{{cite journal|title=The Himalayan Black Bulbul. ''Hypsipetes psaroides''|author=Page, WT|pages=209\u2013211| url=https://archive.org/stream/aviculturalmagaz01avic#page/209/mode/1up|journal=Avicultural Magazine|volume=1|issue=6|year=1903}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"pcr\">{{cite book |title=Birds of South Asia. The Ripley Guide. Volume 2|author1=Rasmussen PC|author2=JC Anderton|publisher=Smithsonian Institution & Lynx Edicions|year=2005|pages=342\u2013344|lastauthoramp=yes}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=raza>{{cite journal|author=Raza, RH |year=1993| title= Sighting of Black Bulbul ''Hypsipetes madagascariensis'' (P.L.S. Muller) in Gaya, Bihar| journal= ''Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society'' |volume=90|issue=2|page= 291|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48609546}}</ref>\n\n<ref name = Warren>Warren BH, Bermingham E, RP Prys-Jones & C Thebaud (2005) Tracking island colonization history and phenotypic shifts in Indian Ocean bulbuls (''Hypsipetes'': Pycnonotidae). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 85:271\u2013287 [http://stri.si.edu/bermingham/Publications/papers/biff_papers/EB,%20Avian%20Bulbuls%20BJLS%202005.pdf PDF]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q998240}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:bulbul, black}}\n[[Category:Hypsipetes|black bulbul]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Himalayas]]\n[[Category:Birds of Eastern Himalaya]]\n[[Category:Birds of China]]\n[[Category:Birds of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Birds of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Birds of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1789|black bulbul]]\n", "name_user": "MeegsC", "label": "safe", "comment": "correct param", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_bulbul"}
{"title_page": "2020 in Hungary", "text_new": "{{Year in Hungary|2020}}\n\nThe following lists events in the year '''[[2020]] in [[Hungary]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[President of Hungary|President]]: [[J\u00e1nos \u00c1der]]\n*[[Prime Minister of Hungary|Prime Minister]]: [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]]\n*[[List of Speakers of the National Assembly (Hungary)|Speaker of the National Assembly]]: [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 K\u00f6v\u00e9r]]\n\n==Events==\n\n===March===\n* 30 March \u2013 the [[National Assembly (Hungary)|Hungarian parliament]] voted in favor of passing legislation that would create a state of emergency without a time limit, grant Prime Minister [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]] the ability to rule by decree, the suspension of parliament with no elections, and prison sentences for spreading fake news and leaving quarantine.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.dw.com/en/hungary-passes-law-allowing-viktor-orban-to-rule-by-decree/a-52956243 |title=Hungary passes law allowing Viktor Orban to rule by decree |date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330144536/https://www.dw.com/en/hungary-passes-law-allowing-viktor-orban-to-rule-by-decree/a-52956243 |archive-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sport===\n*12 to 25 January \u2013 The [[2020 Women's European Water Polo Championship]] is held in [[Budapest]].\n*14 to 26 January \u2013 The [[2020 Men's European Water Polo Championship]] is held in Budapest.\n*24 to 26 January \u2013 The [[2020 European Short Track Speed Skating Championships]] is scheduled to be held in [[Debrecen]].\n*11 to 24 May \u2013 The [[2020 European Aquatics Championships]] is scheduled to be held in Budapest.\n\n==Deaths==\n[[File:J\u00e1nos Acz\u00e9l mathematician 1970.jpg |thumb |right |100 px | [[J\u00e1nos Acz\u00e9l (mathematician)|J\u00e1nos Acz\u00e9l]] ]]\n\n*1 January \u2013 [[J\u00e1nos Acz\u00e9l (mathematician)|J\u00e1nos Acz\u00e9l]], Hungarian-Canadian mathematician (b. 1924).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://uwaterloo.ca/pure-mathematics/news/we-remember-distinguished-professor-emeritus-janos-aczel |title=We remember Distinguished Professor Emeritus J\u00e1nos Aczel |website=uwaterloo.ca |language= |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*4 January \u2013 [[K\u00e1roly Gesztesi]], actor (b. 1963).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://index.hu/kultur/2020/01/04/meghalt_gesztesi_karoly/ |title=Meghalt Gesztesi K\u00e1roly |website=index.hu |language=hu |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*12 January \u2013 [[Mikl\u00f3s Vet\u0151]], Hungarian-born French philosopher (b. 1936).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rtv.rs/hu/kult%C3%BAra/elhunyt-vet%C5%91-mikl%C3%B3s-filoz%C3%B3fus_1083419.html |title=Elhunyt Vet\u0151 Mikl\u00f3s filoz\u00f3fus |website=rtv.rs |language=hu |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*16 January \u2013 [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Iv\u00e1n]], psychiatrist and politician (b. 1933).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://minap.hu/cikk/elhunyt-ivan-laszlo-professzor-gonc-diszpolgara |title=Elhunyt Iv\u00e1n L\u00e1szl\u00f3 professzor , G\u00f6nc d\u00edszpolg\u00e1ra |website=minap.hu |language=hu |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*1 February \u2013 [[P\u00e9ter Andorai]], actor (b. 1948).\n*12 February \u2013 [[Tam\u00e1s Wichmann]], sprint canoeist (b. 1948).\n*24 February \u2013 [[Istv\u00e1n Csuk\u00e1s]], writer and poet (b. 1936).\n*29 February \u2013 [[\u00c9va Sz\u00e9kely]], swimmer (b. 1927).\n*1 March \u2013 [[Istv\u00e1n Balsai]], politician and jurist (b. 1947).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Hungary}}\n{{Year in Europe|2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Hungary| ]]\n[[Category:2020s in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Hungary]]\n[[Category:2020 in Europe|Hungary]]\n[[Category:2020 by country|Hungary]]\n", "text_old": "{{Year in Hungary|2020}}\n\nThe following lists events in the year '''[[2020]] in [[Hungary]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[President of Hungary|President]]: [[J\u00e1nos \u00c1der]]\n*[[Prime Minister of Hungary|Prime Minister]]: [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]]\n*[[List of Speakers of the National Assembly (Hungary)|Speaker of the National Assembly]]: [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 K\u00f6v\u00e9r]]\n\n==Events==\n\n===March===\n* 30 March \u2013 the [[National Assembly (Hungary)|Hungarian parliament]] voted in favor of passing legislation that would create a state of emergency without a time limit, grant Prime Minster [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]] the ability to rule by decree, the suspension of parliament with no elections, and prison sentences for spreading fake news and leaving quarantine.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.dw.com/en/hungary-passes-law-allowing-viktor-orban-to-rule-by-decree/a-52956243 |title=Hungary passes law allowing Viktor Orban to rule by decree |date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330144536/https://www.dw.com/en/hungary-passes-law-allowing-viktor-orban-to-rule-by-decree/a-52956243 |archive-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sport===\n*12 to 25 January \u2013 The [[2020 Women's European Water Polo Championship]] is held in [[Budapest]].\n*14 to 26 January \u2013 The [[2020 Men's European Water Polo Championship]] is held in Budapest.\n*24 to 26 January \u2013 The [[2020 European Short Track Speed Skating Championships]] is scheduled to be held in [[Debrecen]].\n*11 to 24 May \u2013 The [[2020 European Aquatics Championships]] is scheduled to be held in Budapest.\n\n==Deaths==\n[[File:J\u00e1nos Acz\u00e9l mathematician 1970.jpg |thumb |right |100 px | [[J\u00e1nos Acz\u00e9l (mathematician)|J\u00e1nos Acz\u00e9l]] ]]\n\n*1 January \u2013 [[J\u00e1nos Acz\u00e9l (mathematician)|J\u00e1nos Acz\u00e9l]], Hungarian-Canadian mathematician (b. 1924).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://uwaterloo.ca/pure-mathematics/news/we-remember-distinguished-professor-emeritus-janos-aczel |title=We remember Distinguished Professor Emeritus J\u00e1nos Aczel |website=uwaterloo.ca |language= |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*4 January \u2013 [[K\u00e1roly Gesztesi]], actor (b. 1963).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://index.hu/kultur/2020/01/04/meghalt_gesztesi_karoly/ |title=Meghalt Gesztesi K\u00e1roly |website=index.hu |language=hu |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*12 January \u2013 [[Mikl\u00f3s Vet\u0151]], Hungarian-born French philosopher (b. 1936).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rtv.rs/hu/kult%C3%BAra/elhunyt-vet%C5%91-mikl%C3%B3s-filoz%C3%B3fus_1083419.html |title=Elhunyt Vet\u0151 Mikl\u00f3s filoz\u00f3fus |website=rtv.rs |language=hu |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*16 January \u2013 [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Iv\u00e1n]], psychiatrist and politician (b. 1933).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://minap.hu/cikk/elhunyt-ivan-laszlo-professzor-gonc-diszpolgara |title=Elhunyt Iv\u00e1n L\u00e1szl\u00f3 professzor , G\u00f6nc d\u00edszpolg\u00e1ra |website=minap.hu |language=hu |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*1 February \u2013 [[P\u00e9ter Andorai]], actor (b. 1948).\n*12 February \u2013 [[Tam\u00e1s Wichmann]], sprint canoeist (b. 1948).\n*24 February \u2013 [[Istv\u00e1n Csuk\u00e1s]], writer and poet (b. 1936).\n*29 February \u2013 [[\u00c9va Sz\u00e9kely]], swimmer (b. 1927).\n*1 March \u2013 [[Istv\u00e1n Balsai]], politician and jurist (b. 1947).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Hungary}}\n{{Year in Europe|2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Hungary| ]]\n[[Category:2020s in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Hungary]]\n[[Category:2020 in Europe|Hungary]]\n[[Category:2020 by country|Hungary]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "secularisation in action", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_in_Hungary"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Africa}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa \n| map1            = <!--Covid 19 Africa.png-->\n| legend1         = <!--Countries with confirmed cases (red) and deaths (black)<br><small>As of 20 March</small>-->\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = Africa\n| first_case      = Cairo, Egypt\n| arrival_date    = 14 February 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=14|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = <!-- DO NOT CHANGE WITHOUT A SOURCE --> 2,390<ref name=\"bbc\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/resources/idt-4a11d568-2716-41cf-a15e-7d15079548bc |title=Coronavirus in Africa tracker |website=BBC News |language=en-GB |access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| deaths          = <!-- DO NOT CHANGE WITHOUT A SOURCE --> 729<ref name=\"bbc\" /><ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = <!-- DO NOT CHANGE WITHOUT A SOURCE --> 13,912<ref name=\"bbc\" /><ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| suspected_cases =\n| territories     = 56<ref name=\"coronacount\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus update (live) |date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=locations}}\nThe [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to Africa on 14 February 2020. The first confirmed case on the continent was in Egypt,<ref>{{cite news |title=Beijing orders 14-day quarantine for all returnees |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51509248 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Egypt announces first Coronavirus infection |url=https://www.egypttoday.com/Article/1/81641/Egypt-announces-first-Coronavirus-infection |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Egypt Today]]}}</ref> and the first confirmed case in [[sub-Saharan Africa]] was in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nigeria|Nigeria]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Nigeria confirms first coronavirus case |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51671834 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=28 February 2020}}</ref> Most of the identified cases have arrived from Europe and the United States rather than from China.<ref name=\"Africa Braces\">{{cite news |last1=Maclean |first1=Ruth |title=Africa Braces for Coronavirus, but Slowly |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/world/africa/coronavirus-africa-burkina-faso.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nExperts have worried about [[COVID-19]] spreading to Africa, because many of the healthcare systems on the continent are inadequate, having problems such as lack of equipment, lack of funding, insufficient training of healthcare workers, and inefficient data transmission. It was feared that the pandemic could be difficult to keep under control in Africa, and could cause huge economic problems if it spread widely.<ref name=\"African Countries Respond Quickly\">{{cite news |title=African Countries Respond Quickly To Spread Of COVID-19 |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/21/818894991/african-countries-respond-quickly-to-spread-of-covid-19 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=NPR.org |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Africa Braces\"/>\n\n[[Matshidiso Moeti]] of the [[World Health Organization]] said that hand washing and [[physical distancing]] could be challenging in some places in Africa. Lockdowns may not be possible, and challenges may be exacerbated by the prevalence of diseases such as [[malaria]], [[HIV]], [[tuberculosis]], and [[cholera]].<ref name=\"African Countries Respond Quickly\"/> The World Health Organization helped many countries on the continent set up laboratories for [[COVID-19 testing]].<ref name=\"African Countries Respond Quickly\"/> Many preventive measures have been implemented in different countries in Africa, including travel restrictions, flight cancellations, event cancellations,<ref name=\"CNN 2020-03-09\"/> school closures, and border closures.<ref name=\"UN Sees Africa Sliding Into Recession\">{{cite news |title=UN Sees Africa Sliding Into Recession Without Debt-Service Help |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-24/un-sees-africa-sliding-into-recession-without-debt-service-help |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Experts say that experience battling [[Ebola]] helped some countries prepare for COVID-19.<ref name=\"African Countries Respond Quickly\"/><ref name=\"CNN 2020-03-09\">{{cite news |title=Here are the African countries with confirmed coronavirus cases |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/09/africa/nigeria-coronavirus-cases-intl/index.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\nAs of 7 April 2020, two African sovereign states have yet to report a case of COVID-19: [[Comoros]] and [[Lesotho]].<ref name=\"Which countries have yet to confirm coronavirus cases?\">{{cite web|title=Which countries have yet to confirm coronavirus cases?|url=https://en.as.com/en/2020/04/07/other_sports/1586258521_836025.html|accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=[[Diario AS]]}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n=== Total confirmed cases ===\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=700\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x=14 Feb, 15 Feb, 16 Feb, 17 Feb, 18 Feb, 19 Feb, 20 Feb, 21 Feb, 22 Feb, 23 Feb, 24 Feb, 25 Feb, 26 Feb, 27 Feb, 28 Feb, 29 Feb, 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7