 a father and daughter, and were living in France.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-algeria-idUSKBN20P2YK|title=Algeria reports two new coronavirus cases, bringing the total to five|date=2 March 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=2 March 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March, the Ministry of Health recorded 4 new confirmed cases of the coronavirus, all from the same family, bringing the total number to 12 confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ennaharonline.com/%d8%a7%d8%b1%d8%aa%d9%81%d8%a7%d8%b9-%d8%b9%d8%af%d8%af-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%a5%d8%b5%d8%a7%d8%a8%d8%a7%d8%aa-%d8%a7%d9%84%d9%85%d8%a4%d9%83%d8%af%d8%a9-%d8%a8%d9%81%d9%8a%d8%b1%d9%88%d8%b3-%d9%83%d9%88-2/|title=\u0627\u0631\u062a\u0641\u0627\u0639 \u0639\u062f\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0635\u0627\u0628\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0624\u0643\u062f\u0629 \u0628\u0641\u064a\u0631\u0648\u0633 \u0643\u0648\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627 \u0625\u0644\u0649 12 \u062d\u0627\u0644\u0629|date=4 March 2020|website=\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0647\u0627\u0631 \u0623\u0648\u0646\u0644\u0627\u064a\u0646|language=ar|access-date=4 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305134307/https://www.ennaharonline.com/%d8%a7%d8%b1%d8%aa%d9%81%d8%a7%d8%b9-%d8%b9%d8%af%d8%af-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%a5%d8%b5%d8%a7%d8%a8%d8%a7%d8%aa-%d8%a7%d9%84%d9%85%d8%a4%d9%83%d8%af%d8%a9-%d8%a8%d9%81%d9%8a%d8%b1%d9%88%d8%b3-%d9%83%d9%88-2/|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Angola ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Angola}}\n\t\nOn 21 March, the first two cases in the country were confirmed.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://informante.web.na/angola-registered-its-first-coronavirus-case/ | title=Angola registered its first coronavirus case | newspaper=Informant\u00e9 | date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Effective 20 March, all Angolan borders have been closed for 15 days.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://informante.web.na/angola-registered-its-first-coronavirus-case/ | title=Angola closes borders for 15 days | last=Oliveira | first=Yokani | newspaper=[[The Namibian]] | date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Benin ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Benin}}\nOn 16 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Somalia, Liberia, Benin and Tanzania confirm first coronavirus cases|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-africa/somalia-liberia-benin-and-tanzania-confirm-first-coronavirus-cases-idUSKBN2131IA|website=Reuters|date=2020-03-16|accessdate=2020-03-16|language=en|last=|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Botswana===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Botswana}}\nOn 30 March, the first three cases in Botswana were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Botswana registers first Covid-19 cases as three people test positive|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/botswana-registers-first-covid-19-cases-as-three-people-test-positive-45797335|website=www.iol.co.za|date=2020-03-31|accessdate=2020-03-31|language=en|last=|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== Burkina Faso ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Burkina Faso}}\nOn 9 March, the first two cases in the country were reported in Burkina Faso.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2020-03-09/burkina-faso-confirms-first-cases-of-coronavirus|title=Burkina Faso Confirms First Cases of Coronavirus|date=9 March 2020|access-date=9 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the third case was also confirmed, a person who had had direct contact with the first two cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voaafrique.com/a/coronavirus-un-troisi\u00e8me-cas-confirm\u00e9-au-burkina-faso/5328659.html|title=Coronavirus: un troisi\u00e8me cas confirm\u00e9 au Burkina Faso|website=VOA|language=fr|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 14, 2020, a total of 7 cases have been confirmed in the country. 5 of the new confirmed cases had had direct contact with the first two cases. 1 is an English national employed at a gold mine in the country who vacationed in Liverpool and came back on March 10, transiting through Vancouver and Paris .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.burkina24.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-covid-19-7-cas-confirmes-au-burkina/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) : 7 cas confirm\u00e9s au Burkina|last=B24|first=R\u00e9daction|date=2020-03-14|website=L'Actualit\u00e9 du Burkina Faso 24h/24|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n===Burundi===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Burundi}}\nOn 31 March, the first two cases in the country were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|title=East African nation of Burundi confirms first coronavirus cases - Health Ministry|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-burundi/east-african-nation-of-burundi-confirms-first-coronavirus-cases-health-ministry-idUSL8N2BO34B|work=Reuters|date=2020-03-31|accessdate=2020-03-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Cameroon ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cameroon}}\nOn 6 March the first case was confirmed in [[Cameroon]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reuters|accessdate=6 March 2020|title=Cameroon Confirms First Case of Coronavirus|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/06/world/africa/06reuters-health-coronavirus-cameroon.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=6 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|via=NYTimes.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308115724/https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/06/world/africa/06reuters-health-coronavirus-cameroon.html|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Cape Verde ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cape Verde}}\nOn 20 March, the first case in the country was confirmed, a 62 year old from the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cape Verde registers an Adverse Analytical Finding of First COVID-19|url=https://www.insp.gov.cv/index.php/noticias/400-cabo-verde-regista-um-primeiro-caso-positivo-de-covid-19|website=insp.gov.cv |language=English |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Coronav\u00edrus: Ingl\u00eas de 62 anos \u00e9 o primeiro caso confirmado em Cabo Verde|url=https://www.publico.pt/2020/03/20/mundo/noticia/coronavirus-ingles-62-anos-caso-confirmado-cabo-verde-1908619|website=publico.pt |language=Portuguese |date=20 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Central African Republic ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Central African Republic}}\nOn 14 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Central African Republic confirms first coronavirus case -WHO|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-centralafrica/central-african-republic-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-who-idUSL8N2B62KD|website=Reuters|date=2020-03-14|accessdate=2020-03-15|language=en|last=|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Chad===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Chad}}\nOn 19 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reuters|accessdate=19 March 2020|title=Chad confirms first case of coronavirus: government statement|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-chad/chad-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-government-statement-idUSKBN2162LO|date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Democratic Republic of the Congo ===\n[[File:Woman washing hands in DRC - Covid-19.jpg|thumb|The [[MONUSCO]] Force Intervention Brigade has taken measures to boost hygiene to help slow the spread of the virus.]]\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Democratic Republic of the Congo}}\nOn 10 March, the first case was reported in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/democratic-republic-of-congo-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-2|title=Democratic Republic of Congo confirms first coronavirus case {{!}} National Post|last=Health|first=P. M. N.|date=10 March 2020|language=en-CA|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Republic of the Congo ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of the Congo}}\nThe country's first case was announced on 14 March, a 50-year-old man who had returned to the Republic of the Congo from [[Paris]], [[France]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.trust.org/item/20200314231524-ebs0t|title=Congo Republic confirms first coronavirus case -government |date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Djibouti ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Djibouti}}\nOn 18 March, the first case in Djibouti was confirmed.<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n\n=== Egypt ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Egypt}}\n\nEgypt's health ministry announced the first case in the country at [[Cairo International Airport]] involving a Chinese national on 14 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.egypttoday.com/Article/1/81641/Egypt-announces-first-Coronavirus-infection|title=Egypt announces first Coronavirus infection|work=Egypt Today|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215092410/https://www.egypttoday.com/Article/1/81641/Egypt-announces-first-Coronavirus-infection|archive-date=15 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51509248|title=Beijing orders 14-day quarantine for all returnees|publisher=BBC News|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214210032/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51509248|archive-date=14 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, the Egyptian Health Ministry and WHO confirmed 12 new cases of coronavirus infection.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-egypt-idUSKBN20T1IQ|title=Twelve asymptomatic coronavirus cases registered on Nile cruise ship|date=6 March 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=7 March 2020|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307192640/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-egypt-idUSKBN20T1IQ|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The infected persons were among the Egyptian staff aboard the  Nile cruise ship MS ''River Anuket'', which was travelling from Aswan to [[Luxor]]. On 7 March 2020, health authorities announced that 45 people on board had tested positive, and that the ship had been placed in quarantine at a dock in [[Luxor]].<ref name=\"washington.post.1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/uae-raises-virus-cases-to-45-new-cases-from-9-nationalities/2020/03/07/52affb1c-6035-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|title=Egypt says cruise ship quarantined over new virus cluster|first1=Maggie|last1=Michael|first2=Samy Magdy &#124;|last2=AP|website=[[Washington Post]]|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308193805/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/uae-raises-virus-cases-to-45-new-cases-from-9-nationalities/2020/03/07/52affb1c-6035-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Equatorial Guinea ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Equatorial Guinea}}\nOn 14 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Equatorial Guinea announces first coronavirus case |url=https://www.deccanherald.com/international/equatorial-guinea-announces-first-coronavirus-case-813802.html |accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Eritrea===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Eritrea}}\nOn 20 March, the first case in Eritrea was confirmed.<ref name=\"nationalpost.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/angola-eritrea-uganda-confirm-first-cases-as-coronavirus-spreads-in-africa|title=Angola, Eritrea, Uganda confirm first cases as coronavirus spreads in Africa &#124; National Post|first=P. M. N.|last=Health|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Eswatini ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Eswatini}}\nOn 14 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Eswatini-in-Southern-Africa-reports-first-coronavirus-case-620897|title=Eswatini in Southern Africa reports first coronavirus case|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Ethiopia ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ethiopia}}\n\nThe country's first case was announced on 13 March, a Japanese man who had arrived in the country on 4 March from Burkina Faso.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2020-03-13|title=Ethiopia confirms first coronavirus case: Live updates|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/stocks-collapse-coronavirus-global-pandemic-live-200312235606108.html|website=aljazeera.com}}</ref> Three additional cases of the virus were reported on  March 15. The three individuals had close contact with the person who was reported to be infected by the virus on 13 March . Since then eight more confirmed cases were reported by the health ministry to the public, bringing the total to twelve. Among the infected individuals an elderly Ethiopian in her eighties has been said to have some escalating symptoms while other eight have been on a recovery route and showing less and less symptoms of the disease. On March 27, another statement was issued by the health minister stating that four additional cases have been identified while one case being in the [[Adama]] city of the [[Oromia region]]al state and the other three being in [[Addis Ababa]]. Moreover, three more cases were confirmed by the Health Minister on March 31, 2020. Similarly, the following day other three cases were added. On the previous press release the government authorities had noted that one case was retested and confirmed negative and two of the confirmed cases have been sent to their country ([[Japan]]). In aggregate, twenty nine cases are confirmed so far as of 1 April 2020.On April 3, 2020 due to further tests made, six  additional cases have been discovered moving up the tally to thirty five. Measures are being taken by the government and the community together strictly to suppress the further spreading of this deadly virus. Among the six cases identified there were individuals with no traveling history recently, that has made it alarming to the public.<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n\nOn 4 April, three additional cases of the virus were reported. All of the cases were from Addis Ababa. Two of the patients, a 29-year-old and a 34-year-old male Ethiopians, had travel histories to Dubai on different dates. The third case is of a 35-year-old female Ethiopian who had arrived from Sweden on 3 April.[31] On the same date, one additional recovery was reported, increasing the total number of recoveries to 4.[32]\n\nOn 5 April, five more positive cases of the virus were reported. Three of them are Ethiopians. The other two are Libyan and Eritrean nationals.[33]. There are 43 total cases as of April 5, 2020.On april 7 more inndividual detected and totally 54. Among 200+ tests conducted on April 8 2020 , one additonal case has been added to the tally making it 55. With current situation indicating the spread of the virus Ethiopia has declared a state of emergeny.\n\n=== Territories of France===\n{{Further|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n==== Mayotte ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mayotte}}\n\n==== R\u00e9union ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in R\u00e9union}}\n\n=== Gabon ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Gabon}}\nThe country's first case was announced on 12 March, a 27 year old Gabonese man who returned to Gabon from France, 4 days prior to confirmation of the coronavirus. they are really working on preventing more Corona virus case in the country<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/ghana-gabon-confirm-first-cases-of-coronavirus|title=Ghana, Gabon confirm first cases of coronavirus {{!}} National Post|last=Health|first=P. M. N.|date=2020-03-13|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Gambia ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Gambia}}\nThe Gambia reported its first case of coronavirus from a 20-year-old woman who returned from the United Kingdom on 17 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/gambia-reports-first-case-of-coronavirus-health-minister|title=Gambia reports first case of coronavirus -health minister{{!}} National Post|last=Health|first=P. M. N.|date=2020-03-17|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Ghana ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ghana}}\nGhana reported its first two cases on 12 March. The two cases were people who came back to the country from Norway and Turkey, with the contact tracing process beginning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-ghana-gabon-idUSKBN20Z3X9|title=Ghana, Gabon confirm first cases of coronavirus|date=2020-03-13|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-13|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://starrfm.com.gh/2020/03/ghana-confirms-two-coronavirus-cases/|title=Ghana confirms two Coronavirus cases|publisher=[[Starr Fm]]|last=Acheampong|first=Kwame|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, the Minister of Finance, Ken Ofori-Atta, made the cedi equivalent of $100 million available to enhance Ghana's coronavirus preparedness and response plan. Five more cases were confirmed as of 17 March.\nOn 19 March, the Health Minister on his Twitter page tweeted that two more cases were confirmed overnight, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to nine (9) as at 9:00GMT. The health minister said the two cases were both imported. In the afternoon, the confirmed cases increased from 9 to 11 after a test of a 58-year-old Ghanaian woman who is a resident of Kumasi had returned from UK some weeks ago, and another patient, a 61-year-old Lebanese and a resident of Kumasi, showed symptoms of the novel coronavirus and was also tested positive.\nBy 20 March, Ghana had recorded 5 new COVID 19 cases, of which 3 showed no travel history, while the other 2 returned from Paris, France and Amsterdam, moving the total of confirmed cases to 16.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n=== Guinea ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guinea}}\nOn 13 March, Guinea confirmed its first case, an employee of the European Union delegation in Guinea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/13/world/africa/13reuters-health-coronavirus-guinea.html|title=EU Employee Tests Positive for Coronavirus in Guinea's First Case|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Guinea-Bissau ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guinea-Bissau}}\n\nOn 25 March, Guinea-Bissau confirmed its first two COVID-19 cases, a Congolese U.N. employee and an Indian citizen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-bissau/guinea-bissau-confirms-first-two-cases-of-coronavirus-idUSKBN21C2EA|title=Guinea-Bissau confirms first two cases of coronavirus|website=Reuters|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Ivory Coast ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ivory Coast}}\nOn 11 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/world/ivory-coast-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus/news|title=Ivory Coast confirms first case of coronavirus|last=|first=|date=11 March 2020|website=[[Daily Sabah]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Kenya ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kenya}}\nOn 12 March 2020, the first case was confirmed in Kenya by President Uhuru Muigai Kenyatta.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.health.go.ke/kenya-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-four-cs-health/|title=Kenya coronavirus cases rise to four, CS health \u2013 MINISTRY OF HEALTH|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the first case in Kenya was confirmed, a woman who came from the US via London.<ref>{{cite web|author=By ELIZABETH MERAB More by this Author |url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/Kenya-confirms-first-coronavirus-case/1056-5489268-28tqll/index.html |title=Kenya confirms first coronavirus case - VIDEO - Daily Nation |publisher=Nation.co.ke |date= |accessdate=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2020, President Uhuru Kenyatta directed that the following measures to curb COVID-19 be implemented:\n\n* Travel from any countries with any case of Corona virus be restricted.\n* Only Kenyan Citizens, and any foreigners with valid residence permits will be allowed to come into the country provided they proceed on self quarantine or to a government designated quarantine facility.\n* All schools and higher learning institutions be closed by Friday March 20, 2020.\n* Government and businesses people start working from home; except essential services.\n* cashless transactions over cash. Cost of transactions reduced.\n* No congressional meetings \u2013 weddings, malls, night clubs, churches, limitation of visits to hospitals.\n* Hospitals and Shopping malls to give soap and water/hand sanitizers, and regular cleaning of facilities.\n* Cargo vessels, aircraft or ships can come into the country provided they are disinfected at point of departure and the crew quarantined on arrival.\n* UN Headquarters in Kenya  continue operating diplomats travelling to the UN are also exempted from the travel restrictions but observe the self-quarantine rule.\n* A toll-free number (719) set up to report suspected coronavirus cases.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe Health Minister, Mutahi Kagwe banned all social gatherings including religious gatherings on the same date. All flights were banned effective Wednesday 25 March by the Health CS.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n=== Liberia ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Liberia}}\nOn 16 March, the first case in Liberia was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://frontpageafricaonline.com/front-slider/liberia-records-first-case-of-coronavirs-health-authorities-hold-emergency-meeting/|title=Liberia Records First Case of Coronavirus; Health Authorities Hold Emergency Meeting|date=2020-03-16|website=[[FrontPage Africa]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian2020-03-16\"/>\n\n===Libya===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Libya}}\nOn 17 March, in order to prevent the spread of the virus, the UN-recognised [[Government of National Accord]] closed the country's borders, suspended flights for three weeks and banned foreign nationals from entering the country; schools, cafes, mosques and public gatherings have also been closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/libyan-govt-suspends-flights-in-wake-of-covid-19/1768168/|title=Libyan gov't suspends flights in wake of COVID-19|date=2020-03-16|website=Anadolu Agency|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the first case in Libya was confirmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-libya-measures/libya-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-amid-fear-over-readiness-idUSKBN21B2SF|title=Libya confirms first coronavirus case amid fear over readiness|work=[[Reuters]]|date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Madagascar ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Madagascar}}\nOn 20 March, the three first cases were confirmed in Madagascar. All were women.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://actu.orange.mg/officiel-trois-premiers-cas-de-coronavirus-a-madagascar/ |title=Officiel trois premiers cas de Coronavirus \u00e0 Madagascar |work=[[Orange Madagascar]] |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Malawi ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malawi}}\nOn 2 April, the three first cases were confirmed in Malawi.<ref>{{cite web |title=Malawi confirms three cases of coronavirus:Predident Mutharika calls for calm |date=2 April 2020 |url=https://www.nyasatimes.com/malawi-confirms-three-cases-of-coronavirus-president-mutharika-calls-for-calm/ |publisher=Nyasa Times |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Mali ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mali}}\nOn 25 March, the two first cases were confirmed in Mali.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Mali: Authorities confirm first COVID-19 cases March 25 /update 2|url=https://www.garda.com/crisis24/news-alerts/326341/mali-authorities-confirm-first-covid-19-cases-march-25-update-2|work=www.garda.com|date=2020-03-25|accessdate=2020-03-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Mauritania ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mauritania}}\nOn 13 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/mauritania-confirms-first-covid-19-coronavirus-case-12537688|title=Mauritania confirms first coronavirus case|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Mauritius ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mauritius}}\nOn 19 March, the first three cases in the country were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mauritius confirms first three cases of coronavirus|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-mauritius/mauritius-confirms-first-three-cases-of-coronavirus-idUSKBN21541A|website=Reuters|date=2020-03-19|accessdate=2020-03-19|language=en|last=|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== Morocco ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Morocco}}\nOn 2 March, [[Morocco]] recorded its first case of COVID-19. It was a Moroccan national residing in Italy who had returned to Morocco.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2020/03/295120/morocco-records-1st-case-of-coronavirus/|title=Morocco Records First Case of Coronavirus|first=Safaa|last=Kasraoui|date=2 March 2020|access-date=6 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303032405/https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2020/03/295120/morocco-records-1st-case-of-coronavirus/|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Mozambique ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mozambique}}\n\n=== Namibia ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Namibia}}\n\nOn 14 March, the first two cases in the country were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Namibia Says Couple Visiting From Spain Test Positive for Virus|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-14/namibia-says-couple-visiting-from-spain-test-positive-for-virus|website=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]|date=2020-03-14|accessdate=2020-03-14|language=en|last=|publisher=}}</ref> In a first reaction by [[Government of Namibia|government]] air travel to and from Qatar, Ethiopia and Germany was suspended for 30 days. All public and private schools are also closed for a month, and gatherings are restricted to fewer than 50 people. This includes celebrations for the 30th anniversary of [[Independence of Namibia|Namibian independence]] that takes place on 21 March.<ref name=battles>{{Cite news | title=Namibia battles coronavirus | last=Shikongo | first=Arlana | newspaper=[[The Namibian]] | date=16 March 2020 | page=1 | url=https://www.namibian.com.na/89251/read/Namibia-battles-coronavirus}}</ref> Libraries, museums, and art galleries were also closed.<ref name=mayhem>{{Cite news | title=Corona mayhem | last=Nakale | first=Albertina | newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]] | date=16 March 2020 | page=1 | url=https://neweralive.na/posts/corona-mayhem}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, [[President of Namibia|President]] [[Hage Geingob]] declared a [[state of emergency]] as a legal basis to restrict fundamental rights, e.g. to freely move and assemble, guaranteed by the [[Constitution of Namibia|Constitution]].<ref>{{Cite news | title=Govt raises Covid-19 surveillance | last=Ngatjiheue | first=Charmaine | newspaper=[[The Namibian]] | date=18 March 2020 | page=1 | url=https://www.namibian.com.na/89346/read/Govt-raises-Covid-19-surveillance}}</ref>\n\nBy 25 March 2020 the total number of cases reached seven, of which one is thought to be a [[local transmission]]. A 21-day lockdown of the regions of [[Erongo Region|Erongo]] and [[Khomas Region|Khomas]] was announced for 27 March with inter-regional travel forbidden, excluding the commuter towns of [[Okahandja]] and [[Rehoboth, Namibia|Rehoboth]]. Parliament sessions were suspended for the same period, and bars and markets were closed.<ref name=lockdown>{{Cite news | title=Partial lockdown in effect from Friday | last=Shikongo | first=Arlana | newspaper=[[The Namibian]] | date=25 March 2020 | page=1 | url=https://www.namibian.com.na/89582/read/Partial-lockdown-in-effect-from-Friday}}</ref>\n\n===Niger===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Niger}}\nNiger confirmed its first case on 19 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://medicalxpress.com/news/2020-03-niger-coronavirus-case.html |title=Niger announces first coronavirus case |website=medicalxpress.com |language=en-us |access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Nigeria ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nigeria}}\nOn 27 February, [[Nigeria]] confirmed its first case, the first case of coronavirus in [[sub-Saharan Africa]].<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=6 March 2020|title=Nigeria confirms first coronavirus case|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51671834|newspaper=BBC News|date=28 February 2020|via=bbc.co.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302181240/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51671834|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Jason Burke Africa|last1=correspondent|first2=Alison|last2=Rourke|accessdate=6 March 2020|title=Nigeria confirms first coronavirus case in sub-Saharan Africa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/28/coronavirus-found-in-sub-saharan-africa-as-who-says-spread-could-get-out-of-control|newspaper=The Guardian|date=28 February 2020|issn=0261-3077|via=theguardian.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306080437/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/28/coronavirus-found-in-sub-saharan-africa-as-who-says-spread-could-get-out-of-control|archive-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> An Italian citizen who works in Nigeria had returned on 25 February from Milan, Italy through the [[Murtala Muhammed International Airport]], fell ill on 26 February and was transferred to Lagos State Biosecurity Facilities for isolation and testing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ncdc.gov.ng/news/227/first-case-of-corona-virus-disease-confirmed-in-nigeria |title=Nigeria Centre for Disease Control |website=ncdc.gov.ng |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302150128/https://ncdc.gov.ng/news/227/first-case-of-corona-virus-disease-confirmed-in-nigeria |archive-date=2 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51671834 |title=Nigeria confirms first coronavirus case |date=28 February 2020 |website=BBC News |language=en-GB |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302181240/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51671834 |archive-date=2 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"ConfirmedNigeria\" /> The test was confirmed positive by the Virology Laboratory of the [[Lagos University Teaching Hospital]], part of the [[Nigeria Centre for Disease Control]].<ref name=\"Adedokun\">{{Cite journal|last=Mustapha JO, Adedokun KA, Abdullahi IN.|date=|title=Public health preparedness towards COVID-19 outbreak in Nigeria.|url=http://www.apjtm.org/preprintarticle.asp?id=279650|journal=Asian Pacific Journal of Tropical Medicine.|volume=2020;13|pages=|accessdate=<!--28 February 2020 -->|via=Science Direct}}</ref> He was transferred to the Infectious Disease Hospital in [[Yaba, Lagos]].<ref name=\"ConfirmedNigeria\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2020/02/28/breaking-deadly-coronavirus-confirmed-in-lagos-nigeria-at-last/|title=Breaking: Deadly Coronavirus confirmed in Lagos, Nigeria at last|date=25 February 2020|access-date=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228011403/https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2020/02/28/breaking-deadly-coronavirus-confirmed-in-lagos-nigeria-at-last/|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 February, the Lagos State Commissioner for Health announced that the Italian man had travelled on Turkish Airlines with a brief transit at Istanbul.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-nigeria-first-idUSKCN20M1NG|title=Nigeria's first coronavirus case came on flight via Istanbul, went to Ogun state: Lagos health commission|date=28 February 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=29 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229050842/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-nigeria-first-idUSKCN20M1NG|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 6 March, a total of 219 primary and secondary contacts of the index case had been identified and were being actively monitored.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncdc.gov.ng/themes/common/files/sitreps/02ca174a32597a1e20536b86bed723c7.pdf|title=NCDC Situation Report 6 March 2019|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Chloroquine poisoning ==== \nAn official of Nigeria's [[Lagos State]] government has disclosed that hospitals are receiving patients suffering from [[chloroquine]] poisoning where people living in Lagos are overusing the drug as a preventive measure to coronavirus. The excessive usage of chloroquine now endangers lives in Lagos State, Nigeria.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=20 March 2020|title=Chloroquine Poisoning in Lagos|url=https://www.africanews.com/2020/03/20/nigeria-confirms-third-coronavirus-case-index-patient-fully-recovers}}</ref>\n\nOreoluwa Finnih, a Senior Special Assistant to Lagos governor has thus urged the public to desist from using the anti-malaria drug as a measure of preventing coronavirus infection. In Nigeria reports indicate that the drug's price has been hiked since the news broke. Chloroquine has been gaining traction on social media since some news agencies reported it had been approved for the COVID-19 pandemic.\n\n==== Cases of COVID-19 in Nigeria ====\nOn 21 March 2020, ten (10) new cases of COVID-19 in Nigeria were confirmed by the [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)|Federal Ministry of Health, Nigeria]]. It was reported that three (3) new cases in the [[Federal Capital Territory]] (FCT) and seven (7) new cases in Lagos State. This brings the total number of confirmed cases in Nigeria to twenty-two (22).<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=21 March 2020|title=New Cases of COVID-19 Confirmed in Nigeria|url=https://ncdc.gov.ng/news/237/update-on-covid-19-in-nigeria}}</ref>\n\nAll ten (10) new cases are Nigerian nationals. Nine (9) of them have travel history to the United Kingdom, Spain, Netherlands, Canada and France. They returned to the country in the last one week. The tenth case is a close contact of a previously confirmed case. Meanwhile, on the 18 March 2020, the Federal Republic of Nigeria suspended the issuance of visa on arrival to travelers from countries with more than 1,000 cases.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=18 March 2020|title=Nigeria Bans Entry to 13 Countries Highly Invaded by COVID-19 |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/18/africa/nigeria-coronavirus-travel-restrictions-intl/index.html}}</ref> The restriction notice was issued three (3) days before the number of cases of COVID-19 raised to ten (10). The restricted countries include [[China]], [[Italy]], [[Iran]], [[South Korea]], [[Spain]], [[Japan]], [[France]], [[Germany]], the [[United States]], [[Norway]], [[UK]], [[Netherlands]] and [[Switzerland]].\n\n==== Lock-down measures ====\nThe Federal government of Nigeria has instructed institutions to shutdown for 30 days as a lock-down measures and bans to limit the spread of COVID-19. It also banned public gatherings. The state government of Lagos has asked schools to shutdown and banned public gatherings of more than 50 people, particularly religious congregations.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=19 March 2020|title=Nigerian Government Places Lock-down Measures Against COVID-19|url=https://qz.com/africa/1821361/coronavirus-lagos-nigeria-shuts-schools-ban-public-gatherings}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|accessdate=20 March 2020|title=COVID-19: Federal Government Orders Immediate Shutdown of Schools|url=https://nairametrics.com/2020/03/20/covid-19-fg-orders-immediate-shut-down-of-all-schools}}</ref> There was no order from government to shutdown markets and club halls.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nSeveral schools in Nigeria has shutdown, following the directives of the federal government at Abuja. This led the Management of one of the most populated school in Nigeria, the [[Federal Polytechnic, Nekede|Federal Polytechnic Nekede, Owerri]] to dismiss students against COVID-19, stating that the emergency holiday will last for 30 days. The institution had already fixed the dates for the 2019/2020 academic session examination.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=21 March 2020|title=Federal Polytechnic Nekede Dismissed Students Over COVID-19|url=https://allschool.com.ng/nekede-poly-shuts-down-school}}</ref>\n\nThere is much tension in every city in Nigeria as students return to their various homes for fear of contracting COVID-19.\n\n==== High profiled persons with COVID-19 ====\nReports have shown that some high profiled individuals in Nigeria have tested positive for Coronavirus. The Nigeria's high profiled persons hat have tested positive for COVID-19 are: Buhari's chief of staff, [[Abba Kyari]],<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=24 March 2020|title=Buhari's Chief of Staff, Abba Kyari tests Positive for Coronavirus|url=https://guardian.ng/news/buharis-chief-of-staff-abba-kyari-tests-positive-for-coronavirus}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|accessdate=24 March 2020|title=President Tests Negative, Chief of Staff Infected|url=https://www.africanews.com/2020/03/24/nigeria-confirms-third-coronavirus-case-index-patient-fully-recovers}}</ref> Bauchi State governor, [[Bala Muhammed]].<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=24 March 2020|title=Bala Mohammed, Bauchi Governor, Pests Positive for Coronavirus|url=https://businessday.ng/lead-story/article/bala-mohammed-bauchi-governor-tests-positive-for-coronavirus}}</ref>\n\nAs [[Muhammadu Buhari|Muhammadu Buhari's]] closest staff, Nigerians suspected that the president would have the virus as his chief of staff tested positive. Meanwhile, [[Nigeria Centre for Disease Control]] (NCDC) reported that president Buhari tested negative after the test was carried out on him.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=24 March 2020|title=COVID-19: Buhari Tests Negative|url=https://www.africanews.com/2020/03/24/covid-19-buhari-tests-negative-top-aide-tests-positive}}</ref>\n\nIn Nigeria, there are fears everywhere that the Chief of Staff, [[Abba Kyari]] who has tested positive for the coronavirus virus may have transmitted it to more people including Governor [[Yahaya Bello]] of Kogi, Minister of Information, [[Lai Mohammed]], Special Assistant to the President on Media, [[Garba Shehu]]; Minister of Special Duties, [[George Akume]]; Minister of State for FCT, [[Ramatu Tijani]]; [[Geoffrey Onyeama]], and other dignitaries and visitors at the prayers held on March 17, 2020, for the deceased mother of the Kogi State Governor.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThe governor of Kogi State, [[Yahaya Bello]] was tested positive for Coronavirus. Others from the list who met with [[Abba Kyari]] are still under examination to be ascertained if they are negative or positive to the virus.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=25 March 2020|title=Yahaya Bello Tests Positive for Coronavirus|url=https://kogigist.com/2020/03/26/video-those-who-wish-me-to-have-covid-will-have-hiv/}}</ref>\n\n=== Rwanda ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Rwanda}}\nOn 14 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rwanda confirms first case of coronavirus - health ministry|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-rwanda/rwanda-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-health-ministry-idUSKBN2110G0|website=Reuters|date=2020-03-14|accessdate=2020-03-14|language=en|last=|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe}}\nOn 6 April, the first four cases in the country were confirmed.<ref name=\"cgtnafrica 2020-04-06\"/>\n\n=== Senegal ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Senegal}}\nOn 2 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref name=\"senegal.1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lequotidien.sn/coronavirus-le-senegal-enregistre-son-premier-cas/|title=Coronavirus : Le S\u00e9n\u00e9gal enregistre son premier cas &#124; Lequotidien Journal d'informations G\u00e9n\u00e9rales|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Seychelles===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Seychelles}} \nSeychelles reported its first two cases on 14 March. The two cases were people who were in contact with someone in Italy who tested positive.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bonnelame |first1=Betyme |title=2 Seychellois test positive for COVID-19 as globe-sweeping virus reaches island nation|url=http://www.seychellesnewsagency.com/articles/12593/+Seychellois+test+positive+for+COVID-+as+globe-sweeping+virus+reaches+island+nation |accessdate=14 March 2020 |publisher=[[Seychelles News Agency]] |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sierra Leone===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sierra Leone}}\nOn 16 March, the government banned public officials from travelling abroad, and urged citizens to avoid foreign travel.<ref name=\"Sierra Leone ReliefWeb\">{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-18|title=Sierra Leone institutes additional measures in preparedness to prevent and respond to COVID-19|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/sierra-leone/sierra-leone-institutes-additional-measures-preparedness-prevent-and-respond|newspaper=[[Relief Web]]|date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-18|title=Sierra Leone introduces a raft of measures to keep coronavirus out|url=https://www.politicosl.com/articles/sierra-leone-introduces-raft-measures-keep-corona-virus-out|newspaper=Politico SL|date=18 March 2020}}</ref> Quarantine measures are in place for all visitors arriving from countries with more than 50 cases.<ref name=\"Sierra Leone ReliefWeb\" /> Public gatherings of more than 100 people have also been banned.<ref name=\"Sierra Leone ReliefWeb\" /> On 24 March, President [[Julius Maada Bio]] announced a year-long 'state of emergency' in order to deal with a potential outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sierra Leone announces year-long state of emergency despite no confirmed coronavirus|url=http://www.rfi.fr/en/africa/20200325-sierra-leone-announces-year-long-state-of-emergency-despite-no-confirmed-coronavirus|newspaper=RFI|date=25 March 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe president of Sierra Leone confirmed the country's first case of coronavirus on 31 March, a person who traveled from France on 16 March and had been in isolation since.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-31|title=Sierra Leone has confirmed its first case of coronavirus, president says|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-leone-idUSKBN21I1MY|newspaper=Reuters|date=31 March 2020|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n\n===Territories of Spain===\n{{Further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain}}\n\n==== Canary Islands ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canary Islands}}\n\n==== Ceuta ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ceuta}}\n\n==== Melilla ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Melilla}}\n\n===Somalia===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Somalia}}On 16 March, the first case in [[Somalia]] was confirmed.<ref name=\"guardian2020-03-16\"/> Somalia's Health Ministry reported that a Somali citizen was returning home from [[China]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/somalia-tanzania-confirm-first-coronavirus-cases/1767971|title=Somalia, Tanzania confirm first coronavirus cases|date=16 March 2020|work=[[Anadolu Agency]]|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Somaliland====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Somaliland}}\nOn 31 March, the first two cases in [[Somaliland]] was confirmed. The two cases were a Somaliland citizen and a Chinese national.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Somaliland Reports First COVID-19 Cases|url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/somaliland-reports-first-covid-19-cases|work=Voice of America|date=2020-03-31|accessdate=2020-04-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===South Africa===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa}}\nOn 5 March the first confirmed case was announced, returning from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]]<ref name=\"gov.za1\">{{cite web\n|url=https://www.gov.za/speeches/health-reports-first-case-covid-19-coronavirus-5-mar-2020-0000\n|title=Minister Zweli Mkhize reports first case of Covid-19 Coronavirus\n|date=2020-03-05\n|publisher=South African Ministry of Health\n|accessdate=2020-03-06}}</ref> On 15 March 2020, South Africa declared a national state of disaster.<ref name=\"guardian2020-03-16\">{{Cite news\n|last=Burke\n|first=Jason\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/mar/16/african-nations-impose-stricter-measures-as-coronavirus-spreads\n|title=African nations impose stricter measures as coronavirus spreads\n|date=2020-03-16\n|work=[[The Guardian]]\n|access-date=2020-03-16\n|url-status=live\n|language=en-GB\n|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 23 March 2020, President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] issued a national lockdown lasting 21 days from 26 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burke|first=Jason|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/25/coronavirus-cases-africa-pass-amid-fears-health-services-south-who|title=Coronavirus cases in Africa pass 2,400 amid fears for health services|date=2020-03-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-25|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Sudan===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sudan}}\nThe country's first case was announced on 13 March, a man who died in Khartoum on 12 March. He had visited the United Arab Emirates in the first week of March., later it was revealed that the man died because of malaria not Covid-19.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reuters|accessdate=2020-03-13|title=Sudan Reports First Coronavirus Case|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/13/business/13reuters-health-coronavirus-sudan.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=13 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n=== South Sudan ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Sudan}}\nOn 5 April, the first case was confirmed.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{Cite news|url=https://eyeradio.org/south-sudan-confirms-second-covid-19-case/|title=South Sudan confirms second Covid-19 case|date=2020-04-05|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Tanzania ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tanzania}}\nOn 16 March, the first case was confirmed.<ref name=\"guardian2020-03-16\"/>\n\n=== Togo ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Togo}}\nOn 6 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-healthcare-coronavirus-togo/togo-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-idUSKBN20T1Z5 |title=Togo confirms first case of coronavirus |newspaper=Reuters |date=6 March 2020 |access-date=6 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306160438/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-healthcare-coronavirus-togo/togo-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-idUSKBN20T1Z5 |archive-date=6 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Tunisia ===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tunisia}}\nOn 2 March, the first case in the country was confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/italian-returnee-confirmed-tunisias-first-coronavirus-case/|title=Italian returnee confirmed Tunisia's first coronavirus case|access-date=6 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303020158/https://punchng.com/italian-returnee-confirmed-tunisias-first-coronavirus-case/|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"tunisia.1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tap.info.tn/en/Portal-Regions/12418458-gafsa-covid-19|title=Gafsa-COVID-19: legal action taken after two cases fail to comply with home-confinement measures|website=TAP}}</ref>\n \nAs of 28 March, Tunisia currently has 227 confirmed cases.\n\n===Uganda===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uganda}}\nOn 20 March, the first case in Uganda was confirmed.<ref name=\"nationalpost.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/MinofHealthUG/status/1241469504087035904|title=Twitter|website=mobile.twitter.com|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><!-- note that the official Twitter account of the Ministry of Health of Uganda is a reliable source for Ugandan public health news as per WP:TWITTER --><!-- please simply comment out the source if removing the citation, as this is a government source, and likely will be referenced again in the future -->\n\n===Zambia===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Zambia}}\nZambia reported its first 2 cases of COVID-19 on 18 March. The patients were a couple that had travelled to France on holiday.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-18|title=Zambia Confirms 2 Covid-19 cases|url=https://diggers.news/breaking/2020/03/18/zambia-confirms-2-covid-19-cases/|newspaper=News Diggers|date=18 March 2020}}</ref> A third case was recorded on 22 March. The patient was a man who had travelled to Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-22|title=Zambia confirms third coronavirus case|url=https://diggers.news/breaking/2020/03/22/zambia-confirms-third-coronavirus-case/|newspaper=News Diggers|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, President Edgar Lungu confirmed a total of 12 cases during a live national address. He also announced measures which includes suspension of international flights Simon Mwansa Kapwepwe, Harry Mwaanga Nkumbula and Mfuwe International Airports and re-routing of all international flights to Kenneth Kaunda International Airport to facilitate screening of incoming passengers and mandatory quarantine where necessary, closure of all bars, nightclubs, casinos, cinemas and gyms and restriction of all public gatherings to 50 people or less.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-25|title=Lungu's full address: Zambia confirms 12 COVID-19 cases as lock down looms|url=https://diggers.news/local/2020/03/25/lungus-full-address-zambia-records-12-covid-19-cases-as-lock-down-looms/|newspaper=News Diggers|date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 17 March, the government has shut all educational institutions and put in place some restrictions on foreign travel.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-17|title=Government shuts all schools to prevent COVID-19 outbreak|url=https://diggers.news/local/2020/03/17/govt-shuts-all-schools-to-prevent-covid-19-outbreak/|newspaper=News Diggers|date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Zimbabwe===\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Zimbabwe}}\nBefore there were any confirmed cases in the country, President [[Emmerson Mnangagwa]] had declared a national emergency, putting in place travel restrictions and banning large gatherings.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-17|title=Zimbabwe, Namibia Declare National Emergencies Over Virus|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-17/zimbabwe-namibia-declare-national-emergencies-over-coronavirus|newspaper=Bloomberg|date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-17|title=Zimbabwe's President declares COVID-19 a national disaster|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/17/c_138888708.htm|newspaper=[[Xinhua]]|date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The country's defence minister [[Oppah Muchinguri]] caused controversy by stating the coronavirus could be a divine punishment on Western nations for imposing sanctions on Zimbabwe.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2020-03-17|title=Zimbabwe, Namibia Declare National Emergencies Over Virus|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/africa/zimbabwe-minister-coronavirus-gods-punishment-for-west-1.70401945|newspaper=[[GulfNews]]|date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIts first case came from a male resident of [[Victoria Falls]] who travelled from the United Kingdom via South Africa on 15 March. As of 27 March there are 7 confirmed cases in Zimbabwe and 1 death.\n\n==Suspected cases==\n\n=== Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha  ===\nOn 16 March three people who arrived by air to [[Ascension Island]] showed symptoms of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ascension.gov.ac/three-possible-covid-19-cases-identified|title=Three Possible COVID-19 Cases Identified \u2013 Ascension Island Government|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> There is no test equipment on the island but these are isolated at home for 14 days.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 17 March all travel by air to the [[Saint Helena]] island was banned, except for island citizens or residents and similar cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/St-Helena-Travel-Restrictions-in-response-to-the-COVID-19-Virus-18-March-2020.pdf|title=Travel Restrictions in response to the COVID -19 virus|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> There were no known cases on Saint Helena at this time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sainthelena.gov.sh/coronavirus-covid-19-live-qa/|title=Coronavirus (Covid-19): Live Q&A|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March as a precaution the [[Tristan da Cunha Island Council]] on [[Tristan da Cunha]] made the decision to ban visitors to the island to prevent the potential transmission of the disease to islanders.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grundy |first1=Richard |title=Tristan da Cunha Government News: Island Council takes steps to protect island from coronavirus |url=https://www.tristandc.com/government/news-2020-03-15-visitsban.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=www.tristandc.com |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Prevention in other countries==\n\n===Comoros===\nAs of 3 April there have been no reported cases in Comoros. Arriving travellers were to be quarantined for 14 days upon arrival.In order to prevent the spread of the virus, the government has cancelled all incoming flights and banned large gatherings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/foreign-travel-advice/comoros/coronavirus|title=Coronavirus - Comoros travel advice|website=GOV.UK|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Lesotho===\nAs of 3 April there have been no reported cases in Lesotho, but the country doesn't have the ability to test for the virus.<ref name=\"Lesotho declares national emergency\">{{cite web |last1=Ngatane |first1=Nthakoana |title=Lesotho declares national emergency over COVID-19 outbreak |url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/03/19/lesotho-declares-national-emergency-over-covid-19-outbreak |website=ewn.co.za |accessdate=19 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In order to prevent the spread of the virus the government has closed its border with South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/the-star/news/covid-19-lesotho-seals-borders-amid-infection-fears-while-sa-tourism-suffers-44770854|title=Covid-19: Lesotho seals borders amid infection fears while SA tourism suffers|date=2020-03-13|website=IOL|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> On 18 March, the government declared a national emergency despite having no confirmed cases, and closed schools until 17 April (but allowed school meals to continue). Arriving travellers were to be quarantined for 14 days upon arrival.<ref name=\"Lesotho declares national emergency\"/> Prime Minister [[Thomas Thabane]] announced a three-week lock down, commencing from midnight 29 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/africa/2020-03-26-lesotho-to-implement-3-week-lockdown-from-sunday/|title=Covid-19: Lesotho seals borders amid infection fears while SA tourism suffers|date=2020-03-26|website=Sowetan Live|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=27em}}\n*[[412 BC epidemic]]\n*[[1899\u20131923 cholera pandemic]]\n*[[Spanish flu|1918 Spanish flu pandemic]]\n*[[2008 Zimbabwean cholera outbreak]]\n*[[2009\u20132010 West African meningitis outbreak]]\n*[[2012 yellow fever outbreak in Darfur, Sudan]]\n*[[Western African Ebola virus epidemic|2013-16 Western African Ebola virus epidemic]]\n*[[21st century Madagascar plague outbreaks|2014 & 2017 Madagascar plague outbreaks]]\n*[[2016 Angola and DR Congo yellow fever outbreak]]\n*[[Kivu Ebola epidemic|2018 Kivu Ebola epidemic]]\n*[[2019\u20132020 measles outbreak in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]