rica) 1958\u20131979}}\n{{Toyota timeline (North America) 1980\u20132009}}\n{{Modern North American Toyota vehicles}}\n\n[[Category:Toyota vehicles|Supra]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:2020s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1978]]\n[[Category:Hatchbacks]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Touring cars]]\n", "name_user": "Eightsixofakina", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eModels:Fixed typo in engine name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toyota_Supra"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus lockdown in India", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing lockdown in India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|2=current quarantine|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n |title=2020 India coronavirus lockdown\n |image=\n |caption=\n |causes=[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|COVID-19 pandemic in India]]\n |side3=\n |side2=\n |side1=\n |result=The entire country is in lockdown\n |methods=\n{{bulleted list|Ban on people from stepping out of their homes\n|All services and shops closed except hospitals, banks, grocery shops and other essential services\n|Closure of commercial and private establishments (only work-from-home allowed)\n|Suspension of all educational, training, research institutions\n|Closure of all places of worship\n|Suspension of all non-essential public and private transport\n|Prohibition of all social, political, sports, entertainment, academic, cultural, religious activities}}\n |leadfigures1=\n |goals=To contain the spread of coronavirus outbreak in India\n |place=[[India]]|date={{start date|2020|03|25|df=y}} \u2013 present (scheduled to expire on {{end date|2020|04|30|df=yes}})\n |partof=[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n |leadfigures3=\n}}\n\nOn 24 March, the [[Government of India]] under Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] ordered a nationwide [[lockdown]] for 21 days, limiting movement of the entire 1.3 billion population of India as a preventive measure against the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]].<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{Cite news |last=Gettleman |first=Jeffrey |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/world/asia/india-coronavirus-lockdown.html |title=Modi Orders 3-Week Total Lockdown for All 1.3 Billion Indians |date=24 March 2020 |work=The New York Times|last2=Schultz |first2=Kai |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It was ordered after a 14-hour voluntary public curfew on 22 March, followed by enforcement of a series of regulations in the country's COVID-19 affected regions.<ref name=\"UN\">{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/03/1060132 |title=COVID-19: Lockdown across India, in line with WHO guidance |last= |first= |date=2020-03-24 |website=UN News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html |title=India places millions under lockdown to fight coronavirus |author1=Helen Regan |author2=Esha Mitra |author3=Swati Gupta |date= |website=CNN}}</ref> The lockdown was placed when the number of confirmed positive coronavirus cases in India was approximately 500.<ref name=\"NYTimes\"/>\n\nOn 7 April, reports said that the state governments and other advisory committees recommended extending the lockdown.<ref>[https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/close-schools-all-religious-activities-extend-lockdown-states-tell-centre-1664354-2020-04-07 Close schools, all religious activities, extend lockdown: States tell Centre], India Today, 7 April 2020.</ref> On 9 April and  10 April, the State Governments of Odisha and Punjab extended the lockdown in their states to 1 May. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/taking-cues-from-odisha-punjab-extends-lockdown-till-1-may-11586520697517.html|title=Taking cues from Odisha, Punjab extends lockdown till 1 May|last=Anuja|date=2020-04-10|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n[[File:PM Modi's address to the nation on vital aspects relating to COVID-19 menace.webm|thumb|285px|PM Modi's address to the nation prior to the lockdown.]]\n\nThe Government of India confirmed that India's first case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] on 30 January 2020 in the state of [[Kerala]], when a university student from [[Wuhan]] travelled back to the state.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/24/21190868/coronavirus-india-modi-lockdown-kashmir |title=India's coronavirus lockdown and its looming crisis, explained |last=Ward |first=Alex |date=2020-03-24 |website=Vox}}</ref> As the number of confirmed COVID-19 positive cases closed 500, PM Modi on 19 March, asked all citizens to observe '[[Janata Curfew]]' (people's curfew) from 7 am to 9 pm on Sunday, 22 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/pm-modi-calls-for-janta-curfew-on-march-22-from-7-am-9-pm/article31110155.ece |title=PM Modi calls for 'Janata curfew' on March 22 from 7 AM-9 PM |newspaper=BusinessLine}}</ref> At the end of the curfew, Modi had said: \"Janata Curfew is just the beginning of a long battle against COVID-19\". Following this while addressing the nation second time, on 24 March, he announced the nationwide lockdown from midnight of that day, for a period of 21 days.<ref name=\"BBC1\">{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52024239 |title=India's 1.3bn population told to stay at home |date=2020-03-25 |work=BBC News}}</ref> He said that the only solution to control the spread of coronavirus is breaking the cycle of transmission by social distancing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/india-lockdown-pm-narendra-modi-speech-coronavirus-1659266-2020-03-24 |title=21-day lockdown in entire India to fight coronavirus, announces PM Narendra Modi |website=India Today}}</ref> He also added that the lockdown will be enforced more strictly than the Janata Curfew.<ref name=\"PM calls\"/>\n=== Janata curfew ===\nThe Janata curfew was a 14-hour curfew (7am-9pm) that was scheduled for 22 March 2020, prior to the total lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |title=UP Officials Seen With Crowd Amid \"Janata Curfew\". Then, A Clarification |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/up-officials-seen-with-crowd-amid-janata-curfew-then-a-clarification-2198993 |work=NDTV.com}}</ref> Everyone except people of 'essential services' such as police, medical services, media, home delivery professionals and firefighters were needed to take part in the curfew. At 5 pm (22 March 2020), all citizens were asked to stand in their doorways, balconies or windows, and clap their hands or ring their bells in appreciation for the professionals delivering these essential services.<ref name =indiatoday/> People belonging to [[National Cadet Corps (India)|National Cadet Corps]] and [[National Service Scheme]] were to enforce the curfew in the country.<ref name=news18>{{cite news |title=PM Modi Speech on Coronavirus Highlights: Janata Curfew on Sunday, Avoid Panic Buying |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/pm-modi-speech-on-coronavirus-highlights-janata-curfew-on-sunday-avoid-panic-buying-2543315.html |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=News18}}</ref> The Prime Minister also urged the youth to inform 10 others about Janata curfew and encourage everyone to observe the curfew.<ref name=news18/>\n\n== Prohibitions ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar}}\nThe lockdown restricts people from stepping out of their homes.<ref name=\"PM calls\">{{cite web |url=https://pib.gov.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1608009 |title=PM calls for complete lockdown of entire nation for 21 days |last= |first= |date= |website=Press Information Bureau}}</ref> All transport services \u2013 road, air and rail were suspended with exceptions for transportation of essential goods, fire, police and emergency services.<ref name=\"MoHA\">{{cite web |url=https://mha.gov.in/sites/default/files/Guidelines.pdf |title=Guidelines.pdf |last= |first= |date= |website=Ministry of Home Affairs}}</ref> Educational institutions, industrial establishments and hospitality services were also suspended.<ref name=\"MoHA\"/> Services such as food shops, banks and ATMs, petrol pumps, other essentials and their manufacturing are exempted.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tripathi |first=Rahul |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-21-day-lockdown-what-is-exempted-what-is-not/articleshow/74798725.cms |title=India 21 day Lockdown: What is exempted, what is not |date=25 March 2020 |work=The Economic Times}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Home Ministry]] said the anyone who fails to follow the restrictions can face up to a year in jail.<ref name=\"MoHA\"/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n[[File:PM_Modi_conference_on_COVID-19_India_lockdown.jpg|thumb|right|285px|Prime Minister Narendra Modi in a video conference during the lockdown.]]\nOn the first day of the lockdown, nearly all services and factories were suspended.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Singh |first=Karan Deep |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/world/asia/india-lockdown-coronavirus.html |title=India, Day 1: World's Largest Coronavirus Lockdown Begins |date=2020-03-25 |work=The New York Times |last2=Goel |first2=Vindu |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Kumar |first3=Hari |last4=Gettleman |first4=Jeffrey}}</ref> People were hurrying to stock essentials in some parts.<ref>{{Citation |date=24 March 2020 |agency=ANI |title=Covid-19: People flock to wholesale markets in UP, West Bengal amid lockdown |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-people-flock-to-wholesale-markets-in-up-west-bengal-amid-lockdown/videoshow/74787095.cms}}</ref> Arrests across the states were made for violating norms of lockdown such as venturing out for no emergency, opening businesses and home quarantine violations.<ref name=\"IT Day 1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/day-1-of-coronavirus-lockdown-india-registers-88-new-cases-3-deaths-govt-says-working-to-deliver-essential-services-1659742-2020-03-25 |title=Day 1 of coronavirus lockdown: India registers 101 new cases, 3 deaths; Govt says working to deliver essential services |date= |website=India Today}}</ref> The government held meetings with e-commerce websites and vendors to ensure a seamless supply of essential goods across the nation during the lockdown period.<ref name=\"IT Day 1\"/> Several states announced relief funds for the poor and affected people<ref name=\"IT Day 1\"/> while the central government was finalising a stimulus package.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-stimulus-package-for-businesses-poor-modi-govt-1659698-2020-03-25 |title=Rs 2.3 trillion for 1.3 billion: Govt to announce stimulus package to fight coronavirus, says report |date= |website=India Today}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, finance minister [[Nirmala Sitharaman]] announced {{INRConvert |170000|c}} stimulus package to help those affected by the lockdown.<ref name=\"ET relief package\">{{Cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/fm-nirmala-sitharaman-announces-rs-1-7-lakh-crore-relief-package-for-poor/articleshow/74825054.cms?from=mdr |title=FM Nirmala Sitharaman announces Rs 1.7 lakh crore relief package for poor |date=2020-03-27 |work=The Economic Times}}</ref> The package was aimed to provide food security measures for poor households through direct cash transfers, free cereals and [[Fuel gas|cooking gas]] for three months.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/26/coronavirus-india-needs-a-support-package-larger-than-20-billion-dollars.html |title=India announces $22.5 billion stimulus package to help those affected by the lockdown |last=Choudhury |first=Saheli Roy |date=2020-03-26 |website=CNBC}}</ref> It also provided insurance coverage for medical personnel.<ref name=\"ET relief package\"/>\n\nOn 27 March, the [[Reserve Bank of India]] announced a slew of measures to help mitigate the economic impacts of the lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/home-auto-loans-deferred-for-3-months/article31179786.ece |title=RBI cuts rates, allows moratorium on auto, home loan EMIs |date=27 March 2020 |work=The Hindu |issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the announcement of the nationwide lockdown, on March 22, the government had announced that [[Indian Railways]] would suspend passenger operations through March 31.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/india-news/general-news/indian-railways-likely-to-halt-all-trains|title=MASSIVE: Railways suspends all passenger train operations till March 31|last=|first=|website=Republic World|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The national rail network is maintaining its freight operations during the lockdown, to transport essential goods.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/indian-railways-continuing-its-freight-operations-post-22-march-lockdown-11585314775866.html|title=How Indian Railways continuing its freight operations post lockdown|last=Nandi|first=Tamal|date=2020-03-27|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> On 29 March, Indian Railways announced that it would start service for special parcel trains to transport essential goods, in addition to regular freight service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-railways-resumes-parcel-trains-to-transport-essential-goods-11585504148683.html|title=Covid-19: Railways resumes parcel trains to transport essential goods|last=Nandi|first=Shreya|date=2020-03-29|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The national rail operator has also announced plans to convert coaches into isolation wards for patients of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-indian-railways-converts-non-ac-train-coach-into-isolation-ward-on-trial-basis-8201221.html|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Indian Railways converts non-AC train coach into isolation ward on trial basis|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> This has been described as the first time in 167 years that India's rail network had been suspended,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/asia/indian-railways-coronavirus-hospitals-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India has closed its railways for the first time in 167 years. Now trains are being turned into hospitals|first=Hema |last=Ramaprasad|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> although there was also a [[1974 railway strike in India|strike in 1974]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/lr/2002/01/06/stories/2002010600140200.htm |title=Looking back at anger |publisher=The Hindu |date=2002-01-06 |accessdate=2012-02-11}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, the [[Government of Odisha]] extended the lockdown in the state till 30 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/odisha-becomes-first-state-to-extend-covid-19-lockdown-sets-april-30-as-new-date/story-MLEr0Zie3fXZWufT1lC2QM.html|title=Odisha becomes first state to extend Covid-19 lockdown; sets April 30 as new date|date=2020-04-09|publisher=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> On 10 April, the [[Government of Punjab, India|Government of Punjab]] also extended the lockdown till 1 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/india/story/coronavirus-punjab-govt-extends-lockdown-1665578-2020-04-10|title=Coronavirus: Punjab govt extends lockdown till May 1|work=India Today|date=10 April 2020}}</ref> On 11 April, the [[Government of Maharashtra]] extended the lockdown in the state till 30 April.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maharashtra Lockdown At Least Till April 30, Says Uddhav Thackeray |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-lockdown-to-remain-till-april-30-says-maharashtra-chief-minister-uddhav-thackeray-2210114 |website=NDTV |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=11 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\nFood delivery services were banned by several state governments despite central government's approval.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tech.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/internet/zomato-swiggy-ordered-to-shut-down-in-several-states/74828652 |title=Zomato, Swiggy ordered to shut down in several states  |last= |website=ETtech.com}}</ref> Thousands of people emigrated out of major Indian cities, as they became jobless after the lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Priyali Sur |author2=Ben Westcott |title=Indian migrant workers face tough choice amid world's largest lockdown |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/27/india/coronavirus-covid-19-india-2703-intl-hnk/index.html |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=CNN}}</ref> Following the lockdown, India's electricity demand fell down to a five-month low on 28 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/coronavirus-effect-india-s-electricity-demand-falls-to-5-month-low-after-lockdown-1660339-2020-03-27 |title=Coronavirus effect: India's electricity demand falls to 5-month low after lockdown |date= |website=India Today}}</ref>\n\n=== Migrant workers ===\nAn estimated 139 million migrant workers from the countryside work in India's cities and towns. With factories and workplaces shut down, they were left with  no livelihood. In the first few days of the lockdown, television screens captured long processions of migrant workers walking miles to go back to their native villages, often with families and young children on shoulders.<ref>Ismat Ara, [https://thewire.in/labour/watch-no-work-no-money-thousands-stranded-on-anand-vihar-bus-stand Watch | 'No Work, No Money': Thousands Stranded on Anand Vihar Bus Stand], The Wire, 29 March 2020.</ref> Two days later, the Uttar Pradesh government decided to arrange buses at Delhi's [[Anand Vihar ISBT|Anand Vihar bus station]] to take the migrants back to their villages. Large crowds gathered at the bus station awaiting buses. The central government issued a press statement stating that it had asked state governments to set up immediate relief camps for the migrant workers returning to their native states.<ref>[https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/fighting-covid-19-after-the-long-walk-jobless-migrants-head-home-by-bus-120032900041_1.html Fighting Covid-19: After the long walk, jobless migrants head home by bus], Business Standard, 29 March 2020.</ref> On 29 March, the government issued sweeping orders directing that the landlords should not demand rent during the period of the lockdown and that employers should pay wages without deduction. The people that violated the lockdown were to be sent to government-run quarantine facilities for 14 days.<ref>[https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-warns-lockdown-violators-of-14-day-quarantine/article31198038.ece Coronavirus | Migrant workers to be stopped, quarantined at borders, says Centre], The Hindu, 29 March 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/coronavirus-crisis-landlords-can-not-ask-rent-from-students-workers-for-1-month/story/399551.html Coronavirus crisis: Landlords can't ask rent from students, workers for 1 month], Business Today, 29 March 2020.</ref> The [[Supreme Court of India]] agreed to hear a petition on behalf of the migrant workers on 30 March.<ref>[https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/petition-seeking-food-shelter-for-migrants-amid-coronavirus-lockdown-to-be-heard-in-supreme-court-to-2202655?pfrom=home-topstories Supreme Court To Hear Petition On Migrants Amid Lockdown Tomorrow], NDTV, 29 March 2020.</ref>\n[[File:Migrant_workers_stand_in_a_queue_for_food_at_Delhi_Govt_school_during_COVID-19_Lockdown_at_Delhi_IMG_20200331_132400.jpg|thumb|Migrant workers stand in a queue for food at Delhi Govt school during COVID-19 Lockdown at Delhi]]\n\n=== Food supply chain ===\nThe order issued by the Home Ministry on 24 March allowed the functioning of shops dealing with food items as well as the manufacturing units and transportion of \"essential goods\". However, the lack of clarity on \"essential goods\" meant that the policemen on the streets stopped workers going to  factories and the trucks carrying food items. Food industries also faced shortages of labour because the workers were unable to reach workplaces and the factory managers faced the fear of legal action. All these factors combined to result in shortages and a raise in the prices of food items.<ref>Siraj Hussain, [https://thewire.in/economy/covid-19-border-lockdown-how-precariously-placed-are-our-food-supply-chains COVID-19 Border Lockdown: How Precariously Placed are Our Food Supply Chains?], The Wire, 29 March 2020.</ref>\n\n=== Relief ===\nAccording to the Government of India report filed with the Supreme Court of India, state governments operated 22,567 relief camps for stranded migrant workers, of which 15,541 camps (amounting to 68% of all) were operated by Kerala, 1,135 camps by Maharashtra, 178 camps by Tamil Nadu and smaller numbers by other states. [[Non-governmental organisations]] were operating 3,909 camps.<ref>[https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-files-report-on-migrant-workers/article31283896.ece Coronavirus | Centre files report on migrant workers], The Hindu, 7 April 2020.</ref>\n\nBacking the lockdown, the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] provided essential services including soaps, masks and food to many all over India during the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/backing-modi-govt-on-lockdown-rss-doles-out-a-bouquet-of-services-for-those-stranded20200404154059/|title=Backing Modi govt on lockdown, RSS doles out a bouquet of services for those stranded|first=Pragya|last=Kaushika|date=4 April 2020|publisher=ANI|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/rss-gets-ready-to-fight-coronavirus-with-awareness-campaign-masks-soaps-food-packets/386488/|title=RSS gets ready to fight coronavirus with awareness campaign, masks, soaps & food packets|first=Arun|last=Anand|date=24 March 2020|publisher= Printline Media Pvt. Ltd|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article-amp/news-ani/rss-serves-needy-people-in-ap-during-lockdown-120040200150_1.html|title=RSS serves needy people in AP during lockdown|date=2 April 2020|publisher=Business Standard Private Ltd.|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article-amp/news-ani/rss-provides-food-to-needy-operates-52-kitchens-across-delhi-amid-covid-19-lockdown-120032900613_1.html|title=RSS provides food to needy; operates 52 kitchens across Delhi amid COVID-19 lockdown|date=29 March 2020|publisher=Business Standard Private Ltd.|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/helping-hand-rajasthan-rss-workers-join-forces-to-serve-the-poor-amid-coronavirus-lockdown-2564819.html|title=Helping Hand: Rajasthan RSS Workers Join Forces to Serve the Poor Amid Coronavirus Lockdown|date=5 April 2020|publisher=News18.com|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/rss-serves-food-to-over-1-lakh-mumbaikars-during-covid-19-lockdown-821880.html|title=RSS serves food to over 1 lakh Mumbaikars during COVID-19 lockdown|first=Mrityunjay|last=Bose|date=6 April 2020|publisher=The Printers (Mysore) Private Ltd.|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Shiromani Gurdwara Parbandhak Committee]] also offered helping hand amid the coronavirus pandemic to treat corona positive patients at its Hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/sgpc-offers-to-treat-corona-patients-at-its-hospitals-60948 |title=SGPC offers to treat corona patients at its hospitals |work=The Tribune |date=25 March 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/sgpc-offers-to-treat-corona-patients-at-its-hospitals/1779319 |title=SGPC offers to treat corona patients at its hospitals |work=Outlook |date=25 March 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Effectiveness ===\nPeople were seen breaching the lockdown and not following social distancing by crowding in vegetable markets in some places.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Coimbatore/people-throng-vegetable-market-despite-lockdown/article31167795.ece |title=People throng vegetable market despite lockdown |date=2020-03-25 |work=The Hindu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://telanganatoday.com/karimnagar-minister-unhappy-over-people-not-following-social-distancing-norms |title=Karimnagar: Minister unhappy over people not following social distancing norms |website=Telangana Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://theprint.in/opinion/newsmaker-of-the-week/india-did-everything-other-than-social-distancing/389778/ |title=Clapping to slapping \u2014 India did everything other than social distancing this week |last=Rizvi |first=Sumaira |date=2020-03-28 |website=ThePrint}}</ref> On 29 March, Prime Minister Modi advised against this, urging people to stay home in his ''[[Mann Ki Baat]]'' radio address.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/pm-modi-dedicates-mann-ki-baat-address-to-talk-about-coronavirus-crisis-key-highlights/story-kHK3uV1NaIIP9ZasCb2jQO.html |title='I was extremely hurt...': Key highlights of PM Modi's Mann ki Baat address |date=2020-03-29 |website=Hindustan Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March 2020, the police arrested 8 people and registered a complaint against 150 people in [[Hardoi]] for gathering at a mosque.<ref>[https://www.hindustantimes.com/lucknow/lockdown-violation-8-arrested-in-ayodhya-over-150-booked-in-hardoi-for-assembling-in-mosques/story-Kqxj5u6AP6BmGSlRjWpHUK.html Lockdown violation: 8 arrested in Ayodhya, over 150 booked in Hardoi for assembling in mosques - lucknow - Hindustan Times<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On 2 April, 2020, thousands of people assembled at temples in various parts of [[West Bengal]] defying the lockdown for celebrating [[Ram Navami]] and several policemen that attempted to block them were attacked.<ref name=\"The Hindu Ram Navami\"> [https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/kolkata/defying-lockdown-devotees-in-bengal-assemble-at-temples-on-ram-navami/article31237211.ece Defying lockdown, devotees in Bengal assemble at temples on Ram Navami], The Hindu, 2 April 2020.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/devotees-assemble-in-temples-on-ram-navami-in-bengal-defying-lockdown-1662621-2020-04-02|title=Devotees assemble in temples on Ram Navami in Bengal defying lockdown|last=Press Trust of India|first=|date=April 2, 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 12 members of [[Tablighi Jamaat]] were arrested on 5 April 2020 in [[Muzaffarnagar]] for defying the lockdown and organising an event.<ref>[https://www.news18.com/news/india/12-tabligi-jamaat-members-from-nepal-booked-for-defying-lockdown-orders-in-ups-muzaffarnagar-2564823.html 12 Tabligi Jamaat Members from Nepal Booked for Defying Lockdown Orders in UP's Muzaffarnagar - News18<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> A priest in [[Andhra Pradesh]] was arrested for defying the lockdown and organizing a gathering of 150 people in a church.<ref>[https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/andhra-pastor-arrested-for-defying-lockdown-conducting-mass-with-150-people-120040501023_1.html Andhra pastor arrested for defying lockdown, conducting Mass with 150 people | Business Standard News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n[[Henk Bekedam]], [[World Health Organization|WHO]] Representative to India praised the response describing it as \"timely, comprehensive and robust\".<ref name=\"UN\"/> WHO executive director, [[Michael J. Ryan (doctor)|Mike Ryan]] said that lockdowns alone will not eliminate coronavirus. He said that India must take necessary measures to prevent second and third wave of infections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-pandemic-who-india-lockdown-1659803-2020-03-26 |title=Lockdowns alone won't eliminate coronavirus: WHO to India |date= |website=India Today}}</ref> On 3 April 2020, Dr [[David Nabarro]], WHO's special envoy on the disease, said that \u2018Lockdown in India was early, far-sighted and courageous\u2019 and was better than waiting for another 3 or 4 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/lockdown-in-india-was-early-this-was-far-sighted-courageous-move-who-special-envoy-on-covid-19/story-wNdCkNVOqV5gCN8Du9jJ3N.html |title='Lockdown in India was early, far-sighted and courageous': WHO envoy - india news |publisher=Hindustan Times |date= 2 April 2020|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Center for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy|Centre for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy]] (CDDEP) has issued a report in collaboration with [[Johns Hopkins University]] and [[Princeton University]], where it said that a national lockdown is not \"productive\" and could cause \"serious economic damage\". It advocated state-level lockdowns in the most affected states. Its models predicted that in the best case scenario, a peak of one million hospitalisations would be encountered in early June.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/india-may-see-25-crore-covid19-cases-in-next-3-months-report/1781248 |title=India may see 25 crore COVID-19 cases in next 3 months: Report |website=Outlook India}}</ref><ref>Suresh Dharur, Venkataraghavan Srinivasan, [https://thefederal.com/analysis/the-bad-the-worse-and-the-worst-where-india-is-headed-on-coronavirus-graph/ The bad, the worse and the worst: Where India is headed on COVID graph], The Federal, 29 March 2020.</ref><ref>[https://cddep.org/covid-19/ COVID-19 Modeling with IndiaSIM], The Center for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy (CDDEP), 24 March 2020.</ref>{{efn |There was some confusion regarding the involvement of the [[Johns Hopkins University]] as the University said that the use of its logo was unauthorised. However, the University's International Health twitter handle reaffirmed its association with the CDDEP and the report. The [[Princeton University]] also acknowledged the affiliation of its researchers and pointed out that the work will be submitted to peer review.<ref>IANS, [https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/johns-hopkins-university-ties-itself-in-knots-over-alarmist-economist/1783952 Johns Hopkins University ties itself in knots over alarmist economist], Outlook, 29 March 2020.</ref>}} In an op-ed in ''[[The New York Times]]'', the CDDEP director Laxminarayan explained that if the national lockdown finds good compliance, it would reduce the peak infections in early May by 70 to 80 percent, but still 1 million would require hospitalisation and critical care. He further hypothesised, If the lockdown was not imposed the number of critical patients would have reached 5-6 million.<ref>Ramanan Laxminarayan, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/opinion/india-coronavirus-lockdown.html?smid=tw-nytopinion&smtyp=cur What India Needs to Fight the Virus], The New York Times, 27 March 2020.</ref>\n\n[[University of Oxford|Oxford]] COVID-19 Government Response Tracker (OxCGRT) rated India's response to the coronavirus to be most stringent along with South Africa, Israel, New Zealand and Mauritius, scoring 100 in the tracker, and added that India has the strictest lockdown in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/india-implements-strictest-lockdown-in-the-world-lags-in-testing-expert-1665604-2020-04-10|title=India implements strictest lockdown in the world, lags in testing: Expert|date=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/healthcare/study-reveals-indias-response-to-coronavirus-most-stringent-5666531.htm|title=Study reveals India\u2019s response to coronavirus most stringent|date=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 Hubei lockdowns]]\n* [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown]]\n* [[2020 Malaysia movement control order]]\n* [[Curfews and lockdowns related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:Country lockdowns|India]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n[[Category:2020 in India]]\n[[Category:Containment efforts related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing lockdown in India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|2=current quarantine|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n |title=2020 India coronavirus lockdown\n |image=\n |caption=\n |causes=[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|COVID-19 pandemic in India]]\n |side3=\n |side2=\n |side1=\n |result=The entire country is in lockdown\n |methods=\n{{bulleted list|Ban on people from stepping out of their homes\n|All services and shops closed except hospitals, banks, grocery shops and other essential services\n|Closure of commercial and private establishments (only work-from-home allowed)\n|Suspension of all educational, training, research institutions\n|Closure of all places of worship\n|Suspension of all non-essential public and private transport\n|Prohibition of all social, political, sports, entertainment, academic, cultural, religious activities}}\n |leadfigures1=\n |goals=To contain the spread of coronavirus outbreak in India\n |place=[[India]]|date={{start date|2020|03|25|df=y}} \u2013 present (scheduled to expire on {{end date|2020|04|30|df=yes}})\n |partof=[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n |leadfigures3=\n}}\n\nOn 24 March, the [[Government of India]] under Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] ordered a nationwide [[lockdown]] for 21 days, limiting movement of the entire 1.3 billion population of India as a preventive measure against the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]].<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{Cite news |last=Gettleman |first=Jeffrey |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/world/asia/india-coronavirus-lockdown.html |title=Modi Orders 3-Week Total Lockdown for All 1.3 Billion Indians |date=24 March 2020 |work=The New York Times|last2=Schultz |first2=Kai |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It was ordered after a 14-hour voluntary public curfew on 22 March, followed by enforcement of a series of regulations in the country's COVID-19 affected regions.<ref name=\"UN\">{{cite web |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/03/1060132 |title=COVID-19: Lockdown across India, in line with WHO guidance |last= |first= |date=2020-03-24 |website=UN News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html |title=India places millions under lockdown to fight coronavirus |author1=Helen Regan |author2=Esha Mitra |author3=Swati Gupta |date= |website=CNN}}</ref> The lockdown was placed when the number of confirmed positive coronavirus cases in India was approximately 500.<ref name=\"NYTimes\"/>\n\nOn 7 April, reports said that the state governments and other advisory committees recommended extending the lockdown.<ref>[https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/close-schools-all-religious-activities-extend-lockdown-states-tell-centre-1664354-2020-04-07 Close schools, all religious activities, extend lockdown: States tell Centre], India Today, 7 April 2020.</ref> On 9 April and  10 April, the State Governments of Odisha and Punjab extended the lockdown in their states to 1 May. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/taking-cues-from-odisha-punjab-extends-lockdown-till-1-may-11586520697517.html|title=Taking cues from Odisha, Punjab extends lockdown till 1 May|last=Anuja|date=2020-04-10|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n[[File:PM Modi's address to the nation on vital aspects relating to COVID-19 menace.webm|thumb|285px|PM Modi's address to the nation prior to the lockdown.]]\n\nThe Government of India confirmed that India's first case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] on 30 January 2020 in the state of [[Kerala]], when a university student from [[Wuhan]] travelled back to the state.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/24/21190868/coronavirus-india-modi-lockdown-kashmir |title=India's coronavirus lockdown and its looming crisis, explained |last=Ward |first=Alex |date=2020-03-24 |website=Vox}}</ref> As the number of confirmed COVID-19 positive cases closed 500, PM Modi on 19 March, asked all citizens to observe '[[Janata Curfew]]' (people's curfew) from 7 am to 9 pm on Sunday, 22 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/pm-modi-calls-for-janta-curfew-on-march-22-from-7-am-9-pm/article31110155.ece |title=PM Modi calls for 'Janata curfew' on March 22 from 7 AM-9 PM |newspaper=BusinessLine}}</ref> At the end of the curfew, Modi had said: \"Janata Curfew is just the beginning of a long battle against COVID-19\". Following this while addressing the nation second time, on 24 March, he announced the nationwide lockdown from midnight of that day, for a period of 21 days.<ref name=\"BBC1\">{{Cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52024239 |title=India's 1.3bn population told to stay at home |date=2020-03-25 |work=BBC News}}</ref> He said that the only solution to control the spread of coronavirus is breaking the cycle of transmission by social distancing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/india-lockdown-pm-narendra-modi-speech-coronavirus-1659266-2020-03-24 |title=21-day lockdown in entire India to fight coronavirus, announces PM Narendra Modi |website=India Today}}</ref> He also added that the lockdown will be enforced more strictly than the Janata Curfew.<ref name=\"PM calls\"/>\n=== Janata curfew ===\nThe Janata curfew was a 14-hour curfew (7am-9pm) that was scheduled for 22 March 2020, prior to the total lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |title=UP Officials Seen With Crowd Amid \"Janata Curfew\". Then, A Clarification |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/up-officials-seen-with-crowd-amid-janata-curfew-then-a-clarification-2198993 |work=NDTV.com}}</ref> Everyone except people of 'essential services' such as police, medical services, media, home delivery professionals and firefighters were needed to take part in the curfew. At 5 pm (22 March 2020), all citizens were asked to stand in their doorways, balconies or windows, and clap their hands or ring their bells in appreciation for the professionals delivering these essential services.<ref name =indiatoday/> People belonging to [[National Cadet Corps (India)|National Cadet Corps]] and [[National Service Scheme]] were to enforce the curfew in the country.<ref name=news18>{{cite news |title=PM Modi Speech on Coronavirus Highlights: Janata Curfew on Sunday, Avoid Panic Buying |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/pm-modi-speech-on-coronavirus-highlights-janata-curfew-on-sunday-avoid-panic-buying-2543315.html |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=News18}}</ref> The Prime Minister also urged the youth to inform 10 others about Janata curfew and encourage everyone to observe the curfew.<ref name=news18/>\n\n== Prohibitions ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar}}\nThe lockdown restricts people from stepping out of their homes.<ref name=\"PM calls\">{{cite web |url=https://pib.gov.in/PressReleseDetail.aspx?PRID=1608009 |title=PM calls for complete lockdown of entire nation for 21 days |last= |first= |date= |website=Press Information Bureau}}</ref> All transport services \u2013 road, air and rail were suspended with exceptions for transportation of essential goods, fire, police and emergency services.<ref name=\"MoHA\">{{cite web |url=https://mha.gov.in/sites/default/files/Guidelines.pdf |title=Guidelines.pdf |last= |first= |date= |website=Ministry of Home Affairs}}</ref> Educational institutions, industrial establishments and hospitality services were also suspended.<ref name=\"MoHA\"/> Services such as food shops, banks and ATMs, petrol pumps, other essentials and their manufacturing are exempted.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tripathi |first=Rahul |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-21-day-lockdown-what-is-exempted-what-is-not/articleshow/74798725.cms |title=India 21 day Lockdown: What is exempted, what is not |date=25 March 2020 |work=The Economic Times}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Home Ministry]] said the anyone who fails to follow the restrictions can face up to a year in jail.<ref name=\"MoHA\"/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n[[File:PM_Modi_conference_on_COVID-19_India_lockdown.jpg|thumb|right|285px|Prime Minister Narendra Modi in a video conference during the lockdown.]]\nOn the first day of the lockdown, nearly all services and factories were suspended.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Singh |first=Karan Deep |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/world/asia/india-lockdown-coronavirus.html |title=India, Day 1: World's Largest Coronavirus Lockdown Begins |date=2020-03-25 |work=The New York Times |last2=Goel |first2=Vindu |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Kumar |first3=Hari |last4=Gettleman |first4=Jeffrey}}</ref> People were hurrying to stock essentials in some parts.<ref>{{Citation |date=24 March 2020 |agency=ANI |title=Covid-19: People flock to wholesale markets in UP, West Bengal amid lockdown |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-people-flock-to-wholesale-markets-in-up-west-bengal-amid-lockdown/videoshow/74787095.cms}}</ref> Arrests across the states were made for violating norms of lockdown such as venturing out for no emergency, opening businesses and home quarantine violations.<ref name=\"IT Day 1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/day-1-of-coronavirus-lockdown-india-registers-88-new-cases-3-deaths-govt-says-working-to-deliver-essential-services-1659742-2020-03-25 |title=Day 1 of coronavirus lockdown: India registers 101 new cases, 3 deaths; Govt says working to deliver essential services |date= |website=India Today}}</ref> The government held meetings with e-commerce websites and vendors to ensure a seamless supply of essential goods across the nation during the lockdown period.<ref name=\"IT Day 1\"/> Several states announced relief funds for the poor and affected people<ref name=\"IT Day 1\"/> while the central government was finalising a stimulus package.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-stimulus-package-for-businesses-poor-modi-govt-1659698-2020-03-25 |title=Rs 2.3 trillion for 1.3 billion: Govt to announce stimulus package to fight coronavirus, says report |date= |website=India Today}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, finance minister [[Nirmala Sitharaman]] announced {{INRConvert |170000|c}} stimulus package to help those affected by the lockdown.<ref name=\"ET relief package\">{{Cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/fm-nirmala-sitharaman-announces-rs-1-7-lakh-crore-relief-package-for-poor/articleshow/74825054.cms?from=mdr |title=FM Nirmala Sitharaman announces Rs 1.7 lakh crore relief package for poor |date=2020-03-27 |work=The Economic Times}}</ref> The package was aimed to provide food security measures for poor households through direct cash transfers, free cereals and [[Fuel gas|cooking gas]] for three months.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/26/coronavirus-india-needs-a-support-package-larger-than-20-billion-dollars.html |title=India announces $22.5 billion stimulus package to help those affected by the lockdown |last=Choudhury |first=Saheli Roy |date=2020-03-26 |website=CNBC}}</ref> It also provided insurance coverage for medical personnel.<ref name=\"ET relief package\"/>\n\nOn 27 March, the [[Reserve Bank of India]] announced a slew of measures to help mitigate the economic impacts of the lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/home-auto-loans-deferred-for-3-months/article31179786.ece |title=RBI cuts rates, allows moratorium on auto, home loan EMIs |date=27 March 2020 |work=The Hindu |issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the announcement of the nationwide lockdown, on March 22, the government had announced that [[Indian Railways]] would suspend passenger operations through March 31.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/india-news/general-news/indian-railways-likely-to-halt-all-trains|title=MASSIVE: Railways suspends all passenger train operations till March 31|last=|first=|website=Republic World|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The national rail network is maintaining its freight operations during the lockdown, to transport essential goods.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/indian-railways-continuing-its-freight-operations-post-22-march-lockdown-11585314775866.html|title=How Indian Railways continuing its freight operations post lockdown|last=Nandi|first=Tamal|date=2020-03-27|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> On 29 March, Indian Railways announced that it would start service for special parcel trains to transport essential goods, in addition to regular freight service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-railways-resumes-parcel-trains-to-transport-essential-goods-11585504148683.html|title=Covid-19: Railways resumes parcel trains to transport essential goods|last=Nandi|first=Shreya|date=2020-03-29|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The national rail operator has also announced plans to convert coaches into isolation wards for patients of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-indian-railways-converts-non-ac-train-coach-into-isolation-ward-on-trial-basis-8201221.html|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Indian Railways converts non-AC train coach into isolation ward on trial basis|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> This has been described as the first time in 167 years that India's rail network had been suspended,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/05/asia/indian-railways-coronavirus-hospitals-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India has closed its railways for the first time in 167 years. Now trains are being turned into hospitals|first=Hema |last=Ramaprasad|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> although there was also a [[1974 railway strike in India|strike in 1974]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/lr/2002/01/06/stories/2002010600140200.htm |title=Looking back at anger |publisher=The Hindu |date=2002-01-06 |accessdate=2012-02-11}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, the [[Government of Odisha]] extended the lockdown in the state till 30 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/odisha-becomes-first-state-to-extend-covid-19-lockdown-sets-april-30-as-new-date/story-MLEr0Zie3fXZWufT1lC2QM.html|title=Odisha becomes first state to extend Covid-19 lockdown; sets April 30 as new date|date=2020-04-09|publisher=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> On 10 April, the [[Government of Punjab, India|Government of Punjab]] also extended the lockdown till 1 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/india/story/coronavirus-punjab-govt-extends-lockdown-1665578-2020-04-10|title=Coronavirus: Punjab govt extends lockdown till May 1|work=India Today|date=10 April 2020}}</ref> On 11 April, the [[Government of Maharashtra]] extended the lockdown in the state till 30 April.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maharashtra Lockdown At Least Till April 30, Says Uddhav Thackeray |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-lockdown-to-remain-till-april-30-says-maharashtra-chief-minister-uddhav-thackeray-2210114 |website=NDTV |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=11 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\nFood delivery services were banned by several state governments despite central government's approval.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tech.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/internet/zomato-swiggy-ordered-to-shut-down-in-several-states/74828652 |title=Zomato, Swiggy ordered to shut down in several states  |last= |website=ETtech.com}}</ref> Thousands of people emigrated out of major Indian cities, as they became jobless after the lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Priyali Sur |author2=Ben Westcott |title=Indian migrant workers face tough choice amid world's largest lockdown |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/27/india/coronavirus-covid-19-india-2703-intl-hnk/index.html |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=CNN}}</ref> Following the lockdown, India's electricity demand fell down to a five-month low on 28 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/coronavirus-effect-india-s-electricity-demand-falls-to-5-month-low-after-lockdown-1660339-2020-03-27 |title=Coronavirus effect: India's electricity demand falls to 5-month low after lockdown |date= |website=India Today}}</ref>\n\n=== Migrant workers ===\nAn estimated 139 million migrant workers from the countryside work in India's cities and towns. With factories and workplaces shut down, they were left with  no livelihood. In the first few days of the lockdown, television screens captured long processions of migrant workers walking miles to go back to their native villages, often with families and young children on shoulders.<ref>Ismat Ara, [https://thewire.in/labour/watch-no-work-no-money-thousands-stranded-on-anand-vihar-bus-stand Watch | 'No Work, No Money': Thousands Stranded on Anand Vihar Bus Stand], The Wire, 29 March 2020.</ref> Two days later, the Uttar Pradesh government decided to arrange buses at Delhi's [[Anand Vihar ISBT|Anand Vihar bus station]] to take the migrants back to their villages. Large crowds gathered at the bus station awaiting buses. The central government issued a press statement stating that it had asked state governments to set up immediate relief camps for the migrant workers returning to their native states.<ref>[https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/fighting-covid-19-after-the-long-walk-jobless-migrants-head-home-by-bus-120032900041_1.html Fighting Covid-19: After the long walk, jobless migrants head home by bus], Business Standard, 29 March 2020.</ref> On 29 March, the government issued sweeping orders directing that the landlords should not demand rent during the period of the lockdown and that employers should pay wages without deduction. The people that violated the lockdown were to be sent to government-run quarantine facilities for 14 days.<ref>[https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-warns-lockdown-violators-of-14-day-quarantine/article31198038.ece Coronavirus | Migrant workers to be stopped, quarantined at borders, says Centre], The Hindu, 29 March 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/coronavirus-crisis-landlords-can-not-ask-rent-from-students-workers-for-1-month/story/399551.html Coronavirus crisis: Landlords can't ask rent from students, workers for 1 month], Business Today, 29 March 2020.</ref> The [[Supreme Court of India]] agreed to hear a petition on behalf of the migrant workers on 30 March.<ref>[https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/petition-seeking-food-shelter-for-migrants-amid-coronavirus-lockdown-to-be-heard-in-supreme-court-to-2202655?pfrom=home-topstories Supreme Court To Hear Petition On Migrants Amid Lockdown Tomorrow], NDTV, 29 March 2020.</ref>\n[[File:Migrant_workers_stand_in_a_queue_for_food_at_Delhi_Govt_school_during_COVID-19_Lockdown_at_Delhi_IMG_20200331_132400.jpg|thumb|Migrant workers stand in a queue for food at Delhi Govt school during COVID-19 Lockdown at Delhi]]\n\n=== Food supply chain ===\nThe order issued by the Home Ministry on 24 March allowed the functioning of shops dealing with food items as well as the manufacturing units and transportion of \"essential goods\". However, the lack of clarity on \"essential goods\" meant that the policemen on the streets stopped workers going to  factories and the trucks carrying food items. Food industries also faced shortages of labour because the workers were unable to reach workplaces and the factory managers faced the fear of legal action. All these factors combined to result in shortages and a raise in the prices of food items.<ref>Siraj Hussain, [https://thewire.in/economy/covid-19-border-lockdown-how-precariously-placed-are-our-food-supply-chains COVID-19 Border Lockdown: How Precariously Placed are Our Food Supply Chains?], The Wire, 29 March 2020.</ref>\n\n=== Relief ===\nAccording to the Government of India report filed with the Supreme Court of India, state governments operated 22,567 relief camps for stranded migrant workers, of which 15,541 camps (amounting to 68% of all) were operated by Kerala, 1,135 camps by Maharashtra, 178 camps by Tamil Nadu and smaller numbers by other states. [[Non-governmental organisations]] were operating 3,909 camps.<ref>[https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-centre-files-report-on-migrant-workers/article31283896.ece Coronavirus | Centre files report on migrant workers], The Hindu, 7 April 2020.</ref>\n\nBacking the lockdown, the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] provided essential services including soaps, masks and food to many all over India during the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/backing-modi-govt-on-lockdown-rss-doles-out-a-bouquet-of-services-for-those-stranded20200404154059/|title=Backing Modi govt on lockdown, RSS doles out a bouquet of services for those stranded|first=Pragya|last=Kaushika|date=4 April 2020|publisher=ANI|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/rss-gets-ready-to-fight-coronavirus-with-awareness-campaign-masks-soaps-food-packets/386488/|title=RSS gets ready to fight coronavirus with awareness campaign, masks, soaps & food packets|first=Arun|last=Anand|date=24 March 2020|publisher= Printline Media Pvt. Ltd|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article-amp/news-ani/rss-serves-needy-people-in-ap-during-lockdown-120040200150_1.html|title=RSS serves needy people in AP during lockdown|date=2 April 2020|publisher=Business Standard Private Ltd.|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article-amp/news-ani/rss-provides-food-to-needy-operates-52-kitchens-across-delhi-amid-covid-19-lockdown-120032900613_1.html|title=RSS provides food to needy; operates 52 kitchens across Delhi amid COVID-19 lockdown|date=29 March 2020|publisher=Business Standard Private Ltd.|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/helping-hand-rajasthan-rss-workers-join-forces-to-serve-the-poor-amid-coronavirus-lockdown-2564819.html|title=Helping Hand: Rajasthan RSS Workers Join Forces to Serve the Poor Amid Coronavirus Lockdown|date=5 April 2020|publisher=News18.com|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/rss-serves-food-to-over-1-lakh-mumbaikars-during-covid-19-lockdown-821880.html|title=RSS serves food to over 1 lakh Mumbaikars during COVID-19 lockdown|first=Mrityunjay|last=Bose|date=6 April 2020|publisher=The Printers (Mysore) Private Ltd.|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Shiromani Gurdwara Parbandhak Committee]] also offered helping hand amid the coronavirus pandemic to treat corona positive patients at its Hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/sgpc-offers-to-treat-corona-patients-at-its-hospitals-60948 |title=SGPC offers to treat corona patients at its hospitals |work=The Tribune |date=25 March 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/sgpc-offers-to-treat-corona-patients-at-its-hospitals/1779319 |title=SGPC offers to treat corona patients at its hospitals |work=Outlook |date=25 March 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Effectiveness ===\nPeople were seen breaching the lockdown and not following social distancing by crowding in vegetable markets in some places.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Coimbatore/people-throng-vegetable-market-despite-lockdown/article31167795.ece |title=People throng vegetable market despite lockdown |date=2020-03-25 |work=The Hindu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://telanganatoday.com/karimnagar-minister-unhappy-over-people-not-following-social-distancing-norms |title=Karimnagar: Minister unhappy over people not following social distancing norms |website=Telangana Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://theprint.in/opinion/newsmaker-of-the-week/india-did-everything-other-than-social-distancing/389778/ |title=Clapping to slapping \u2014 India did everything other than social distancing this week |last=Rizvi |first=Sumaira |date=2020-03-28 |website=ThePrint}}</ref> On 29 March, Prime Minister Modi advised against this, urging people to stay home in his ''[[Mann Ki Baat]]'' radio address.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/pm-modi-dedicates-mann-ki-baat-address-to-talk-about-coronavirus-crisis-key-highlights/story-kHK3uV1NaIIP9ZasCb2jQO.html |title='I was extremely hurt...': Key highlights of PM Modi's Mann ki Baat address |date=2020-03-29 |website=Hindustan Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March 2020, the police arrested 8 people and registered a complaint against 150 people in [[Hardoi]] for gathering at a mosque.<ref>[https://www.hindustantimes.com/lucknow/lockdown-violation-8-arrested-in-ayodhya-over-150-booked-in-hardoi-for-assembling-in-mosques/story-Kqxj5u6AP6BmGSlRjWpHUK.html Lockdown violation: 8 arrested in Ayodhya, over 150 booked in Hardoi for assembling in mosques - lucknow - Hindustan Times<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On 2 April, 2020, thousands of people assembled at temples in various parts of [[West Bengal]] defying the lockdown for celebrating [[Ram Navami]] and several policemen that attempted to block them were attacked.<ref name=\"The Hindu Ram Navami\"> [https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/kolkata/defying-lockdown-devotees-in-bengal-assemble-at-temples-on-ram-navami/article31237211.ece Defying lockdown, devotees in Bengal assemble at temples on Ram Navami], The Hindu, 2 April 2020.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/devotees-assemble-in-temples-on-ram-navami-in-bengal-defying-lockdown-1662621-2020-04-02|title=Devotees assemble in temples on Ram Navami in Bengal defying lockdown|last=Press Trust of India|first=|date=April 2, 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 12 members of [[Tablighi Jamaat]] were arrested on 5 April 2020 in [[Muzaffarnagar]] for defying the lockdown and organising an event.<ref>[https://www.news18.com/news/india/12-tabligi-jamaat-members-from-nepal-booked-for-defying-lockdown-orders-in-ups-muzaffarnagar-2564823.html 12 Tabligi Jamaat Members from Nepal Booked for Defying Lockdown Orders in UP's Muzaffarnagar - News18<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> A priest in [[Andhra Pradesh]] was arrested for defying the lockdown and organizing a gathering of 150 people in a church.<ref>[https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/andhra-pastor-arrested-for-defying-lockdown-conducting-mass-with-150-people-120040501023_1.html Andhra pastor arrested for defying lockdown, conducting Mass with 150 people | Business Standard News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n[[Henk Bekedam]], [[World Health Organization|WHO]] Representative to India praised the response describing it as \"timely, comprehensive and robust\".<ref name=\"UN\"/> WHO executive director, [[Michael J. Ryan (doctor)|Mike Ryan]] said that lockdowns alone will not eliminate coronavirus. He said that India must take necessary measures to prevent second and third wave of infections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-pandemic-who-india-lockdown-1659803-2020-03-26 |title=Lockdowns alone won't eliminate coronavirus: WHO to India |date= |website=India Today}}</ref> On 3 April 2020, Dr [[David Nabarro]], WHO's special envoy on the disease, said that \u2018Lockdown in India was early, far-sighted and courageous\u2019 and was better than waiting for another 3 or 4 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/lockdown-in-india-was-early-this-was-far-sighted-courageous-move-who-special-envoy-on-covid-19/story-wNdCkNVOqV5gCN8Du9jJ3N.html |title='Lockdown in India was early, far-sighted and courageous': WHO envoy - india news |publisher=Hindustan Times |date= 2 April 2020|accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Center for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy|Centre for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy]] (CDDEP) has issued a report in collaboration with [[Johns Hopkins University]] and [[Princeton University]], where it said that a national lockdown is not \"productive\" and could cause \"serious economic damage\". It advocated state-level lockdowns in the most affected states. Its models predicted that in the best case scenario, a peak of one million hospitalisations would be encountered in early June.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/india-may-see-25-crore-covid19-cases-in-next-3-months-report/1781248 |title=India may see 25 crore COVID-19 cases in next 3 months: Report |website=Outlook India}}</ref><ref>Suresh Dharur, Venkataraghavan Srinivasan, [https://thefederal.com/analysis/the-bad-the-worse-and-the-worst-where-india-is-headed-on-coronavirus-graph/ The bad, the worse and the worst: Where India is headed on COVID graph], The Federal, 29 March 2020.</ref><ref>[https://cddep.org/covid-19/ COVID-19 Modeling with IndiaSIM], The Center for Disease Dynamics, Economics & Policy (CDDEP), 24 March 2020.</ref>{{efn |There was some confusion regarding the involvement of the [[Johns Hopkins University]] as the University said that the use of its logo was unauthorised. However, the University's International Health twitter handle reaffirmed its association with the CDDEP and the report. The [[Princeton University]] also acknowledged the affiliation of its researchers and pointed out that the work will be submitted to peer review.<ref>IANS, [https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/johns-hopkins-university-ties-itself-in-knots-over-alarmist-economist/1783952 Johns Hopkins University ties itself in knots over alarmist economist], Outlook, 29 March 2020.</ref>}} In an op-ed in ''[[The New York Times]]'', the CDDEP director Laxminarayan explained that if the national lockdown finds good compliance, it would reduce the peak infections in early May by 70 to 80 percent, but still 1 million would require hospitalisation and critical care. He further hypothesised, If the lockdown was not imposed the number of critical patients would have reached 5-6 million.<ref>Ramanan Laxminarayan, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/opinion/india-coronavirus-lockdown.html?smid=tw-nytopinion&smtyp=cur What India Needs to Fight the Virus], The New York Times, 27 March 2020.</ref>\n\n[[University of Oxford|Oxford]] COVID-19 Government Response Tracker (OxCGRT) rated India's response to the coronavirus to be most stringent along with South Africa, Israel, New Zeland and Mauritius, scoring 100 in the tracker, and added that India has the strictest lockdown in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/india-implements-strictest-lockdown-in-the-world-lags-in-testing-expert-1665604-2020-04-10|title=India implements strictest lockdown in the world, lags in testing: Expert|date=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/healthcare/study-reveals-indias-response-to-coronavirus-most-stringent-5666531.htm|title=Study reveals India\u2019s response to coronavirus most stringent|date=11 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 Hubei lockdowns]]\n* [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown]]\n* [[2020 Malaysia movement control order]]\n* [[Curfews and lockdowns related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:Country lockdowns|India]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n[[Category:2020 in India]]\n[[Category:Containment efforts related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|India]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: New Zeland \u2192 New Zealand", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_lockdown_in_India"}
{"title_page": "Agria", "text_new": "{{about||the insect genus|Agria (fly)|the city in Hungary|Eger}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox Greek Dimos\n|name               = Agria\n|name_local         = \u0391\u03b3\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\n|image_map          = DE Agrias.svg \n|map_caption        = Location within the regional unit\n|image_skyline      = Agria, Magnesia.JPG\n|caption_skyline    = \n|city_flag          = \n|city_seal          = \n|coordinates        = {{coord|39|22|N|23|02|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|elevation          = \n|periph             = [[Thessaly]]\n|periphunit         = [[Magnesia (regional unit)|Magnesia]]\n|municipality = [[Volos]]\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|pop_municunit      = 5632\n|pop_community      = 5191\n|area_municunit     = 25.2\n|postal_code        = 373 00\n|area_code          = 2428\n|licence            = &Beta;&Omicron;\n|website            = \n}}\n'''Agria''' ({{lang-el|\u0391\u03b3\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac}}) is a town and a former [[Communities and Municipalities of Greece|municipality]] in [[Magnesia (regional unit)|Magnesia]], [[Thessaly]], [[Greece]]. Since the 2011 local government reform it is part of the municipality [[Volos]], of which it is a municipal unit.<ref name=Kallikratis>[http://www.kedke.gr/uploads2010/FEKB129211082010_kallikratis.pdf Kallikratis law] Greece Ministry of Interior {{in lang|el}}</ref> The municipal unit has an area of 25.227&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=stat01>{{cite web|url=http://dlib.statistics.gr/Book/GRESYE_02_0101_00098%20.pdf |publisher=National Statistical Service of Greece |title=Population & housing census 2001 (incl. area and average elevation) |language=el |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921212047/http://dlib.statistics.gr/Book/GRESYE_02_0101_00098%20.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-21 }}</ref> It lies on the [[Pelion]] peninsula about 7&nbsp;km from [[Volos]].\n\n== Name ==\nThere are some different opinions about the town's name. Some believe that the name comes from wild olive trees (Agrielies) (\u0391\u03b3\u03c1\u03b9\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03ad\u03c2), or a small plant named \"Agriada\" ({{lang-el|\u0391\u03b3\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1}}). A scholar named Patroklos Palamidas from the nearby village of Lechonia said that the name originated from an ancient temple, which existed in the region and was dedicated to Agrea Dimitra ({{lang-el|\u0391\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03af\u03b1 \u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03b7\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1}}).\n\n== Ottoman occupation (1423-1881) ==\nDuring the Turkish occupation in Agria there were few settlements such as a hostel for caravans and a toll station. However, houses were built in the early 19th century, before the Revolution of 1821. It is relatively new town (the community was established in 1912). The area formerly belonged to the villages of Drakia and Agios Laurentios, a port from which these and other villages distributed agricultural and craft products.\n\n== Economic growth ==\n[[File:Agria, Magnesia(02).JPG|thumb|left|180px|Panoramic view.]]\n\nFrom 1809 - 1860 companies were created that exported local crafts and copper to Western Europe, Romania, and Russia.\n\nAgria started to grow rapidly after the annexation of Thessaly from the Turks, and with the construction of a coastal road and rail network during 1895 that connected Volos to the southwestern villages of Pelion, which exported sea fruit, oil, and black olives from the bay.\n\n[[File:Agria train station.jpg|thumb|left|180px|The [[Agria railway station|train station]].]]\n\nIn 1911 the international cement plant A.G.E.T HERCULES ({{lang-el|\u0391.\u0393.\u0395.\u03a4 \u0397\u03a1\u0391\u039a\u039b\u0397\u03a3}}) was founded there. The plant occupies a natural harbor and is among the largest cement producers in Europe, Asia, and America.\n\nIn 1920 an English commercial paper stated that Agria was \u00abthe largest port in the world\u00bb with reference to their exports of olives and oil. Around two hundred thousand kilos (200 tons) of table olives are exported annually from Agria.\n\nA new wave of residents moved to Agria in 1922 when refugees from Asia Minor, mainly Eastern Thrace, took shelter there after their expulsion from their home land.\n\n20th century Agria saw population and industrial growth. The famous EPSA ({{lang-el|\u0395\u03a8\u0391}}) founded in 1924 by the Kosmadopoulos brothers, who owned a bank, built a refrigerated fruit and ice plant. The overproduction of lemons in the already developed movement of traditional lemonade from Asia Minor sellers, leading owners to recruit a German engineer for running drink bottling plant. The legend is the German engineer has discovered a rare recipe for the production of lemonade, recipe still used today is unchanged and the company's stock.<br />\n \nOther local businesses were founded and flourished then as the factories of packaging and trade of olives, the wood processing industry which was originally craft construction barrels and the modernization of the industry turned to woodworking and furniture at the same time. Other smaller companies also mostly oil warehouses - have begun to operate and attract people to Agria.\n\n== WWII Italian and German occupation (1941-1944) ==\n[[File:Agria, administration1ag7.jpeg|thumb|160px|WWII administration.]]\n[[File:Agria, vrisi.jpeg|thumb|160px|A fountain of Agria. The crack on this water tap came by a bullet of a German soldiers rifle.]]\n\nFrom June 1941 until September 1943 the village was base for the Italian occupation forces. From October 1943 until September 1944 Agria was the home and base for operations of a company of the 4th Polizei Waffen SS field engineers, the 16th Coy SS Pz. Gren. Rgt 8. The commanders building still exists. It is a neoclassical house located at the center of Agria next to the church of Saint George (Agios Georgios).\n\n== Tourism ==\n\nIn the summer months it becomes a popular tourist destination. The large beach at Agria and at nearby Soutrali beach are good for swimming. The chapels of Timios Stavros, Panaghia Goritsa and Panaghia Tripa, built within the rocks, are remarkable for their beauty and simplicity. At the end of July exhibitions of popular art and local dances take place. Also in the middle of summer when there is a new moon there is a celebration in honor of the fishermen ''(psaradiki vradia)'' where fresh [[Kakavia (soup)|kakavia]] (traditional fish soup) is served. The area used to have many olive groves which, unfortunately enough, have now mainly been replaced by modern buildings.\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Vangelis]] (1943\u2013), composer\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n*[http://www.agria.gr/ Municipality of Agria (no longer being updated)]\n\n{{Volos div}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Pelion]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Magnesia (regional unit)]]\n", "text_old": "{{For2|the insect genus|[[Agria (fly)]]|the city in Hungary|[[Eger]]}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox Greek Dimos\n|name               = Agria\n|name_local         = \u0391\u03b3\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\n|image_map          = DE Agrias.svg \n|map_caption        = Location within the regional unit\n|image_skyline      = Agria, Magnesia.JPG\n|caption_skyline    = \n|city_flag          = \n|city_seal          = \n|coordinates        = {{coord|39|22|N|23|02|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|elevation          = \n|periph             = [[Thessaly]]\n|periphunit         = [[Magnesia (regional unit)|Magnesia]]\n|municipality = [[Volos]]\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|pop_municunit      = 5632\n|pop_community      = 5191\n|area_municunit     = 25.2\n|postal_code        = 373 00\n|area_code          = 2428\n|licence            = &Beta;&Omicron;\n|website            = \n}}\n'''Agria''' ({{lang-el|\u0391\u03b3\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac}}) is a town and a former [[Communities and Municipalities of Greece|municipality]] in [[Magnesia (regional unit)|Magnesia]], [[Thessaly]], [[Greece]]. Since the 2011 local government reform it is part of the municipality [[Volos]], of which it is a municipal unit.<ref name=Kallikratis>[http://www.kedke.gr/uploads2010/FEKB129211082010_kallikratis.pdf Kallikratis law] Greece Ministry of Interior {{in lang|el}}</ref> The municipal unit has an area of 25.227&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=stat01>{{cite web|url=http://dlib.statistics.gr/Book/GRESYE_02_0101_00098%20.pdf |publisher=National Statistical Service of Greece |title=Population & housing census 2001 (incl. area and average elevation) |language=el |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921212047/http://dlib.statistics.gr/Book/GRESYE_02_0101_00098%20.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-21 }}</ref> It lies on the [[Pelion]] peninsula about 7&nbsp;km from [[Volos]].\n\n== Name ==\nThere are some different opinions about the town's name. Some believe that the name comes from wild olive trees (Agrielies) (\u0391\u03b3\u03c1\u03b9\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03ad\u03c2), or a small plant named \"Agriada\" ({{lang-el|\u0391\u03b3\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1}}). A scholar named Patroklos Palamidas from the nearby village of Lechonia said that the name originated from an ancient temple, which existed in the region and was dedicated to Agrea Dimitra ({{lang-el|\u0391\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03af\u03b1 \u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03b7\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1}}).\n\n== Ottoman occupation (1423-1881) ==\nDuring the Turkish occupation in Agria there were few settlements such as a hostel for caravans and a toll station. However, houses were built in the early 19th century, before the Revolution of 1821. It is relatively new town (the community was established in 1912). The area formerly belonged to the villages of Drakia and Agios Laurentios, a port from which these and other villages distributed agricultural and craft products.\n\n== Economic growth ==\n[[File:Agria, Magnesia(02).JPG|thumb|left|180px|Panoramic view.]]\n\nFrom 1809 - 1860 companies were created that exported local crafts and copper to Western Europe, Romania, and Russia.\n\nAgria started to grow rapidly after the annexation of Thessaly from the Turks, and with the construction of a coastal road and rail network during 1895 that connected Volos to the southwestern villages of Pelion, which exported sea fruit, oil, and black olives from the bay.\n\n[[File:Agria train station.jpg|thumb|left|180px|The [[Agria railway station|train station]].]]\n\nIn 1911 the international cement plant A.G.E.T HERCULES ({{lang-el|\u0391.\u0393.\u0395.\u03a4 \u0397\u03a1\u0391\u039a\u039b\u0397\u03a3}}) was founded there. The plant occupies a natural harbor and is among the largest cement producers in Europe, Asia, and America.\n\nIn 1920 an English commercial paper stated that Agria was \u00abthe largest port in the world\u00bb with reference to their exports of olives and oil. Around two hundred thousand kilos (200 tons) of table olives are exported annually from Agria.\n\nA new wave of residents moved to Agria in 1922 when refugees from Asia Minor, mainly Eastern Thrace, took shelter there after their expulsion from their home land.\n\n20th century Agria saw population and industrial growth. The famous EPSA ({{lang-el|\u0395\u03a8\u0391}}) founded in 1924 by the Kosmadopoulos brothers, who owned a bank, built a refrigerated fruit and ice plant. The overproduction of lemons in the already developed movement of traditional lemonade from Asia Minor sellers, leading owners to recruit a German engineer for running drink bottling plant. The legend is the German engineer has discovered a rare recipe for the production of lemonade, recipe still used today is unchanged and the company's stock.<br />\n \nOther local businesses were founded and flourished then as the factories of packaging and trade of olives, the wood processing industry which was originally craft construction barrels and the modernization of the industry turned to woodworking and furniture at the same time. Other smaller companies also mostly oil warehouses - have begun to operate and attract people to Agria.\n\n== WWII Italian and German occupation (1941-1944) ==\n[[File:Agria, administration1ag7.jpeg|thumb|160px|WWII administration.]]\n[[File:Agria, vrisi.jpeg|thumb|160px|A fountain of Agria. The crack on this water tap came by a bullet of a German soldiers rifle.]]\n\nFrom June 1941 until September 1943 the village was base for the Italian occupation forces. From October 1943 until September 1944 Agria was the home and base for operations of a company of the 4th Polizei Waffen SS field engineers, the 16th Coy SS Pz. Gren. Rgt 8. The commanders building still exists. It is a neoclassical house located at the center of Agria next to the church of Saint George (Agios Georgios).\n\n== Tourism ==\n\nIn the summer months it becomes a popular tourist destination. The large beach at Agria and at nearby Soutrali beach are good for swimming. The chapels of Timios Stavros, Panaghia Goritsa and Panaghia Tripa, built within the rocks, are remarkable for their beauty and simplicity. At the end of July exhibitions of popular art and local dances take place. Also in the middle of summer when there is a new moon there is a celebration in honor of the fishermen ''(psaradiki vradia)'' where fresh [[Kakavia (soup)|kakavia]] (traditional fish soup) is served. The area used to have many olive groves which, unfortunately enough, have now mainly been replaced by modern buildings.\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Vangelis]] (1943\u2013), composer\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n*[http://www.agria.gr/ Municipality of Agria (no longer being updated)]\n\n{{Volos div}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Pelion]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Magnesia (regional unit)]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agria"}
{"title_page": "Tsolak MLKE-Galstyan", "text_new": "{{short description|Armenian choreographer and dancer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tsolak MLKE-Galstyan\n| image              = \u053f\u0578\u0574\u056b\u057f\u0561\u057d\u056b 10 \u057a\u0561\u057f\u057e\u056b\u0580\u0561\u0576\u0576\u0565\u0580\u0568 1.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \"Komitas 10 Commandments\" emotional dance. contemporary dance performance\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = [[February]] [[25]], [[1984]]\n| birth_place        = [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[Armenian]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = [[Choreographer]], [[Dancer]], [[Director]], [[Painter]], [[Playwright]], [[Art Manager]]\n| known_for          = \n| website            = http://mihrtheatre.com/ \n}}\n\n'''Tsolak MLKE-Galstyan''' ([[February]] [[25]], [[1984]], [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]]), [[Armenian]] choreographer, painter, director, dancer, playwright, art manager, founder and artistic director of [[Mihr (theatre)|Mihr (theatre)- the first Contemporary Dance Company in Armenia]]. Tsolak MLKE-Galstyan is considered to be the founder of [[contemporary dance]] in Armenia.<ref>[https://rusneb.ru/catalog/000202_000054_712266/ \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0415\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 (2013)\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0446 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430]/</ref> He is the son of the Armenian sculptor, painter and ceramist Hrachya Galstyan.\n\n== Education ==\n*[[2020]] participated in [http://www.lairarts.com/multidisciplinary-residency.html/ \"Multidisciplinary Residency Program: Revisiting the Roaring Twenties 1920/2020: Art, Culture and the [[\u00c9cole de Paris]]\"], organized by [http://www.lairarts.com/ L'Air Arts], [[Paris]], [[France]].<ref>[http://www.lairarts.com/tsolak-galstyan.html/ Tsolak MLKE-Galstyan\u2019s page in L\u2019Air Arts website]/</ref>\n*[[2012]] participated in the [[Physically integrated dance|Inclusive Dance]] workshops organized by [[British Council]], led by  [[Candoco Dance Company]] (UK) in [[Armenia]]\n*[[2009]] studied the \u201cOpen Circle\u201d method at the \u201cOpen Circle\u201d theatre in [[Lithuania]].\n*[[2008]] Studied The Theatre Management Program organized by the Cambridge-Yerevan Sister City Association (U.S. Community Connections Program) in  [[Boston]], [[Cambridge]], [[New York]], [[USA]].                 \n*[[2006]] studied Contemporary Dance at the ''Duncan'' Center in [[Prague]], the [[Czech Republic]].\n*[[2006]] participated in the Interactive Theatre Courses led by Careen Chapman (UK) in [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]]\n*[[2006]] attended Dance Philosophy Courses led by [[Modris Tenisons]] in [[Riga]], [[Latvia]].\n*[[2001]]-[[2007]] graduate from the Graphics Department of the [[Yerevan State Academy of Fine Arts]]: he has studied [[Graphic Design]].\n*[[1996]]-[[2002]] studied acting skills at \u201cYelq\u201d Experimental Artist Theatre.\n*[[1998]]-[[2000]] graduated  from ''Mkhitar Sebastatsi'' Art College / Honored student.\n*[[1998]] started his retraining and committed to contemporary dance.\n*[[1992]] started attending classical dance courses.\n*[[1990]] started practicing traditional Armenian dances, parallelly  studied Latino-American dance.\n\n== Career ==\n*[[2003]] founded [[Mihr (theatre)|MIHR Contemporary Dance Company]] with his sister Shoghakat MLKE-Galstyan and became its artistic director, choreographer and soloist.<ref>[http://mihrtheatre.com/about-us/ Tsolak MLKE-Galstyan\u2019s biography in the website of MIHR Theatre]</ref> He also leads his studio at MIHR theatre, where he teaches contemporary dance, dance theatre and stage movement.\n*[[2005]]\u2013till present -Open-air and special events Manager and Curator of  Dance Platform at [https://highfest.am/ HIGH FEST International Performing Arts Festival]  in Yerevan, Armenia.<ref>[https://soundcloud.com/armradio/01102018a-3/ \u054e\u0565\u0580\u0576\u0561\u057f\u0578\u0582\u0576.\u0551\u0578\u056c\u0561\u056f \u0544\u056c\u0584\u0565-\u0533\u0561\u056c\u057d\u057f\u0575\u0561\u0576]</ref><ref>[https://www.arvest.am/content/%D5%A9%D5%A1%D5%BF%D5%A5%D6%80%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%A1%D5%B6-%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%BE%D5%A5%D5%BD%D5%BF%D5%AB-%D5%B6%D5%B8%D6%80-%D5%B0%D5%B8%D6%80%D5%AB%D5%A6%D5%B8%D5%B6%D5%B6%D5%A5%D6%80%D5%A8-%D5%B8%D6%80-%D5%BF%D5%A5%D5%BD%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%A5%D5%AC%D5%AB-%D5%A4%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%B1%D5%A1%D5%B6-%D5%B0%D5%A1%D5%B5%D6%86%D5%A5%D5%BD%D5%BF-6-%D6%80%D5%A4-%D5%B4%D5%AB%D5%BB%D5%A1%D5%A6%D5%A3%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%AB%D5%B6-%D6%83%D5%A1%D5%BC%D5%A1%D5%BF%D5%B8%D5%B6%D5%AB/ \u0540\u0561\u057d\u0574\u056b\u056f \u0540\u0578\u057e\u0570\u0561\u0576\u0576\u056b\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576/\u0539\u0561\u057f\u0565\u0580\u0561\u056f\u0561\u0576 \u0561\u0580\u057e\u0565\u057d\u057f\u056b \u0576\u0578\u0580 \u0570\u0578\u0580\u056b\u0566\u0578\u0576\u0576\u0565\u0580\u0568, \u0578\u0580 \u057f\u0565\u057d\u0561\u0576\u0565\u056c\u056b \u0564\u0561\u0580\u0571\u0561\u0576 \u0540\u0531\u0545\u0556\u0535\u054d\u054f 6-\u0580\u0564 \u0574\u056b\u057b\u0561\u0566\u0563\u0561\u0575\u056b\u0576 \u0583\u0561\u057c\u0561\u057f\u0578\u0576\u056b \u0577\u0576\u0578\u0580\u0570\u056b\u057e]</ref><ref>[https://armeniasputnik.am/culture/20161005/5079130/hayastan-lehastan-par.html/ \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0576 \u0578\u0582 \u053c\u0565\u0570\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0568 \u0562\u0561\u0580\u0565\u056f\u0561\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u00ab\u057a\u0561\u0580\u0561\u0575\u056b\u0576\u00bb \u056f\u0561\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0580\u057b \u0565\u0576 \u057d\u057f\u0565\u0572\u056e\u0578\u0582\u0574]</ref>\n*[[2017]]-till present- works as a lecturer of  the Master Course ''Contemporary Dance Improvisation'' at the [[Armenian State Pedagogical University]] <ref>[http://dancedep.bu.am/am/team.html/ \u0551\u0578\u056c\u0561\u056f \u0544\u056c\u0584\u0565 \u0533\u0561\u056c\u057d\u057f\u0575\u0561\u0576-\u0540\u054a\u0544\u0540 \u054a\u0561\u0580\u0561\u0580\u057e\u0565\u057d\u057f\u056b \u0574\u0561\u0576\u056f\u0561\u057e\u0561\u0580\u056a\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0561\u0574\u0562\u056b\u0578\u0576\u056b \u0564\u0561\u057d\u0561\u056d\u0578\u057d]</ref>\n*[[2011]]-[[2017]]  has led \u201cDance as an Emotion\u201d and \u201cMovement as an Emotion\u201d master classes in [[Poland]] ([[Olsztyn]]), [[USA]] ([[Albuquerque]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Calabasas]], [[Ventura]]), [[Iran]] ([[Isfahan]], [[Tehran]]), [[Russia]] ([[Ivanovo]], [[St. Petersburg]]).\n*[[2015]] has been the Festival Art. Director of the \u201cAsank Anank\u201d Syrian-Armenian Youth Integration Festival in Yerevan, Armenia.<ref>[https://aleppo-ngo.org/hy/%D5%BD%D5%AB%D6%80%D5%AB%D5%A1%D5%B0%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%A9%D5%B5%D5%A1%D5%B6-%D5%B4%D5%B7%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%B5%D5%A9%D5%AB-%D6%85%D6%80%D5%A5%D6%80%D5%AB%D5%B6-%D5%B6%D5%BE%D5%AB/ \u054d\u056b\u0580\u056b\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0574\u0577\u0561\u056f\u0578\u0582\u0575\u0569\u056b \u0585\u0580\u0565\u0580\u056b\u0576 \u0576\u057e\u056b\u0580\u057e\u0561\u056e \u0583\u0561\u057c\u0561\u057f\u0578\u0576 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0574]</ref><ref>[http://www.archmuseum.am/?p=1814/ \u0531\u057d\u0561\u0576\u0584-\u0531\u0576\u0561\u0576\u0584 \u0583\u0561\u057c\u0561\u057f\u0578\u0576\u0568 \u0587 \u0543\u0561\u0580\u057f\u0561\u0580\u0561\u057a\u0565\u057f\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0561\u0566\u0563\u0561\u0575\u056b\u0576 \u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0561\u0580\u0561\u0576-\u056b\u0576\u057d\u057f\u056b\u057f\u0578\u0582\u057f\u0568]</ref>\n*[[2011]]-[[2012]] worked as a Theatre Expert in the \u201cArmenian-Turkish Reconciliation Project\u201d in [[Mu\u015f]] ([[Turkey]]) \u0587 [[Gyumri]] ([[Armenia]]).\n\nTsolak MLKE-Galstyan is a member of [https://www.ietm.org/ IETM- International network for contemporary performing arts].<ref>[https://www.ietm.org/en/satellite-cairo-2018/session/whos-disabled/ Satellite Cairo-2018-Session: Who's Disabled]</ref><ref>[http://www.panarmenian.net/m/arm/news/67652/ \u00ab\u0544\u056b\u0570\u0580\u00bb \u0569\u0561\u057f\u0580\u0578\u0576\u0568 \u0574\u0561\u057d\u0576\u0561\u056f\u0581\u0565\u0581 IETM-\u056b \u0569\u057e\u0578\u057e 30-\u0580\u0564 \u0561\u0574\u0565\u0576\u0561\u0574\u0575\u0561 \u0570\u0561\u0574\u0561\u056a\u0578\u0572\u0578\u057e\u056b\u0576]</ref>\n\n== Performances ==\nTsolak MLKE-Galstyan is the choreographer of  21 performances of  [[Mihr (theatre)|MIHR Contemporary Dance Company]] and Art. Director of more than 70 shows.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m60aJiLJUWg/ CV - \u0544\u053b\u0540\u0550 \u0539\u0531\u054f\u0550\u0548\u0546` \u054a\u0561\u0580\u056b \u0578\u0582\u056a\u0576 \u0578\u0582 \u056f\u056b\u0580\u0584\u0568]</ref>\n \n*2018 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-song-of-a-refugee-2018//\"The Song of a Refugee\"] (\u054fite-specific Contemporary Dance Performance) \n*2017 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/we/\"We\"] (Inclusive Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2015 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/lavash/\"Lavash\"] (Physical Performance. Contemporary Dance)\n*2015 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/names/\"Names\"] (Emotional Dance. Contemporary Dance)\n*2014 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-fly/\"The Fly\"] (\u054fite-specific Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2014 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/no-more-lies-2014/\"No More Lies\"] (\u054fite-specific Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2013 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-sound-of-loneliness-2013/\"The Sound of Loneliness\"] (Music of Movement)\n*2012 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/soldiers-2012/\"Soldiers\"] (Contemporary Dance)\n*2012 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/conversation-of-thoughts-2012/\"Conversation of Thoughts\"] (Open-air Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2011 ''Plays about Death'' [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-murderer-2011/\"The Murderer\"], [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-mortally-ill-2011/\"The Mortally Ill\"], [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-suicidal-2011/\"The Suicidal\"] (Contemporary Dance)\n*2010 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/dreams-in-dreams-2010/\"Dreams in Dreams\"] (Contemporary Dance)\n*2010 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/black-castle-2010/\"Black Castle\"] (Open-air Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2009 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/komitas-10-commandments-2009/\"Komitas 10 Commandments\"] (Emotional Dance. Contemporary Dance) \n*2008 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/sasna-tsrer-sanasar-and-baghdasar-2008/\"Sasna Tsrer. Sanasar and Baghdasar\"] (Multimedia, Ethno-Modern Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2007 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-colors-2007/\"The Colors\"] (Action-Painting Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2006 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/am-i-crazy-2006/\"Am I Crazy?\"] (Drama Dance. Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2005 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/roots-2005/\"Roots\"] (Open-air Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2004 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/creation-2004/\"Creation\"] (Phosphoric Movement Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2003 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/which-is-our-guilt-god-2003/\"Which is our Guilt, God?\"] (Open-air Contemporary Dance Performance)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*\u0412\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0415\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 (2013). ''\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0446 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430. \u00ab\u0411\u0410\u041b\u0415\u0422\u00bb. ''{{ISBN|978-5-901818-12-1}}\n*Next Stage Europe 3 (2017). ''Contemporary Theatrical Texts by  Armenian, Georgian, Azerbaijani and Russian playwrights. Graf & Graf.''\n\n==External links==\n*[http://mihrtheatre.com/ Official Website] \n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B5N59ES_Fn8/ Where does the dance begin?: Tsolak Mlke-Galstyan at TEDxYerevan]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OEHE5y7HBd0/ \u053b\u0574 \u0563\u0580\u0561\u0564\u0561\u0580\u0561\u0576\u0568. \u0551\u0578\u056c\u0561\u056f \u0544\u056c\u0584\u0565-\u0533\u0561\u056c\u057d\u057f\u0575\u0561\u0576]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:MLKE-Galstyan, Tsolak}}\n[[Category:Contemporary dance choreographers]]\n[[Category:Armenian directors]]\n[[Category:Armenian dancers]]\n[[Category:Armenian painters]]\n[[Category:Armenian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Choreographers]]\n[[Category:Dance in Armenia]]\n[[Category:Contemporary dance companies]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Armenian choreographer and dancer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tsolak MLKE-Galstyan\n| image              = \u053f\u0578\u0574\u056b\u057f\u0561\u057d\u056b 10 \u057a\u0561\u057f\u057e\u056b\u0580\u0561\u0576\u0576\u0565\u0580\u0568 1.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \"Komitas 10 Commandments\" emotional dance. contemporary dance performance\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = [[February]] [[25]], [[1984]]\n| birth_place        = [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[Armenian]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = [[Choreographer]], [[Dancer]], [[Director]], [[Painter]], [[Playwright]], [[Art Manager]]\n| known_for          = \n| website            = http://mihrtheatre.com/ \n}}\n\n'''Tsolak MLKE-Galstyan''' ([[February]] [[25]], [[1984]], [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]]), [[Armenian]] choreographer, painter, director, dancer, playwright, art manager, founder and artistic director of [[Mihr (theatre)|Mihr (theatre)- the first Contemporary Dance Company in Armenia]]. Tsolak MLKE-Galstyan is considered to be the founder of [[contemporary dance]] in Armenia.<ref>[https://rusneb.ru/catalog/000202_000054_712266/ \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0415\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 (2013)\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0446 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430]/</ref> He is the son of the Armenian sculptor, painter and ceramist Hrachya Galstyan. \n\n== Education ==\n*[[2020]] participated in [http://www.lairarts.com/multidisciplinary-residency.html/ \"Multidisciplinary Residency Program: Revisiting the Roaring Twenties 1920/2020: Art, Culture and the [[\u00c9cole de Paris]]\"], organized by [http://www.lairarts.com/ L'Air Arts], [[Paris]], [[France]]. <ref>[http://www.lairarts.com/tsolak-galstyan.html/ Tsolak MLKE-Galstyan\u2019s page in L\u2019Air Arts website]/</ref>\n*[[2012]] participated in the [[Physically integrated dance|Inclusive Dance]] workshops organized by [[British Council]], led by  [[Candoco Dance Company]] (UK) in [[Armenia]]\n*[[2009]] studied the \u201cOpen Circle\u201d method at the \u201cOpen Circle\u201d theatre in [[Lithuania]].\n*[[2008]] Studied The Theatre Management Program organized by the Cambridge-Yerevan Sister City Association (U.S. Community Connections Program) in  [[Boston]], [[Cambridge]], [[New York]], [[USA]].                 \n*[[2006]] studied Contemporary Dance at the ''Duncan'' Center in [[Prague]], the [[Czech Republic]].\n*[[2006]] participated in the Interactive Theatre Courses led by Careen Chapman (UK) in [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]]\n*[[2006]] attended Dance Philosophy Courses led by [[Modris Tenisons]] in [[Riga]], [[Latvia]].\n*[[2001]]-[[2007]] graduate from the Graphics Department of the [[Yerevan State Academy of Fine Arts]]: he has studied [[Graphic Design]].\n*[[1996]]-[[2002]] studied acting skills at \u201cYelq\u201d Experimental Artist Theatre.\n*[[1998]]-[[2000]] graduated  from ''Mkhitar Sebastatsi'' Art College / Honored student.\n*[[1998]] started his retraining and commited to contemporary dance.\n*[[1992]] started attending classical dance courses.\n*[[1990]] started practicing traditional Armenian dances, parallelly  studied Latino-American dance.\n\n== Career ==\n*[[2003]] founded [[Mihr (theatre)|MIHR Contemporary Dance Company]] with his sister Shoghakat MLKE-Galstyan and became its artistic director, choreographer and soloist. <ref>[http://mihrtheatre.com/about-us/ Tsolak MLKE-Galstyan\u2019s biography in the website of MIHR Theatre]</ref>. He also leads his studio at MIHR theatre, where he teaches contemporary dance, dance theatre and stage movement.\n*[[2005]]\u2013till present -Open-air and special events Manager and Curator of  Dance Platform at [https://highfest.am/ HIGH FEST International Performing Arts Festival]  in Yerevan, Armenia. <ref>[https://soundcloud.com/armradio/01102018a-3/ \u054e\u0565\u0580\u0576\u0561\u057f\u0578\u0582\u0576.\u0551\u0578\u056c\u0561\u056f \u0544\u056c\u0584\u0565-\u0533\u0561\u056c\u057d\u057f\u0575\u0561\u0576]</ref> <ref>[https://www.arvest.am/content/%D5%A9%D5%A1%D5%BF%D5%A5%D6%80%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%A1%D5%B6-%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%BE%D5%A5%D5%BD%D5%BF%D5%AB-%D5%B6%D5%B8%D6%80-%D5%B0%D5%B8%D6%80%D5%AB%D5%A6%D5%B8%D5%B6%D5%B6%D5%A5%D6%80%D5%A8-%D5%B8%D6%80-%D5%BF%D5%A5%D5%BD%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%A5%D5%AC%D5%AB-%D5%A4%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%B1%D5%A1%D5%B6-%D5%B0%D5%A1%D5%B5%D6%86%D5%A5%D5%BD%D5%BF-6-%D6%80%D5%A4-%D5%B4%D5%AB%D5%BB%D5%A1%D5%A6%D5%A3%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%AB%D5%B6-%D6%83%D5%A1%D5%BC%D5%A1%D5%BF%D5%B8%D5%B6%D5%AB/ \u0540\u0561\u057d\u0574\u056b\u056f \u0540\u0578\u057e\u0570\u0561\u0576\u0576\u056b\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576/\u0539\u0561\u057f\u0565\u0580\u0561\u056f\u0561\u0576 \u0561\u0580\u057e\u0565\u057d\u057f\u056b \u0576\u0578\u0580 \u0570\u0578\u0580\u056b\u0566\u0578\u0576\u0576\u0565\u0580\u0568, \u0578\u0580 \u057f\u0565\u057d\u0561\u0576\u0565\u056c\u056b \u0564\u0561\u0580\u0571\u0561\u0576 \u0540\u0531\u0545\u0556\u0535\u054d\u054f 6-\u0580\u0564 \u0574\u056b\u057b\u0561\u0566\u0563\u0561\u0575\u056b\u0576 \u0583\u0561\u057c\u0561\u057f\u0578\u0576\u056b \u0577\u0576\u0578\u0580\u0570\u056b\u057e]</ref><ref>[https://armeniasputnik.am/culture/20161005/5079130/hayastan-lehastan-par.html/ \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0576 \u0578\u0582 \u053c\u0565\u0570\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0568 \u0562\u0561\u0580\u0565\u056f\u0561\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u00ab\u057a\u0561\u0580\u0561\u0575\u056b\u0576\u00bb \u056f\u0561\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0580\u057b \u0565\u0576 \u057d\u057f\u0565\u0572\u056e\u0578\u0582\u0574]</ref>\n*[[2017]]-till present- works as a lecturer of  the Master Course ''Contemporary Dance Improvisation'' at the [[Armenian State Pedagogical University]] <ref>[http://dancedep.bu.am/am/team.html/ \u0551\u0578\u056c\u0561\u056f \u0544\u056c\u0584\u0565 \u0533\u0561\u056c\u057d\u057f\u0575\u0561\u0576-\u0540\u054a\u0544\u0540 \u054a\u0561\u0580\u0561\u0580\u057e\u0565\u057d\u057f\u056b \u0574\u0561\u0576\u056f\u0561\u057e\u0561\u0580\u056a\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0561\u0574\u0562\u056b\u0578\u0576\u056b \u0564\u0561\u057d\u0561\u056d\u0578\u057d]</ref>\n*[[2011]]-[[2017]]  has led \u201cDance as an Emotion\u201d and \u201cMovement as an Emotion\u201d master classes in [[Poland]] ([[Olsztyn]]), [[USA]] ([[Albuquerque]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Calabasas]], [[Ventura]]), [[Iran]] ([[Isfahan]], [[Tehran]]), [[Russia]] ([[Ivanovo]], [[St. Petersburg]]).\n*[[2015]] has been the Festival Art. Director of the \u201cAsank Anank\u201d Syrian-Armenian Youth Integration Festival in Yerevan, Armenia. <ref>[https://aleppo-ngo.org/hy/%D5%BD%D5%AB%D6%80%D5%AB%D5%A1%D5%B0%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%A9%D5%B5%D5%A1%D5%B6-%D5%B4%D5%B7%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%B5%D5%A9%D5%AB-%D6%85%D6%80%D5%A5%D6%80%D5%AB%D5%B6-%D5%B6%D5%BE%D5%AB/ \u054d\u056b\u0580\u056b\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0574\u0577\u0561\u056f\u0578\u0582\u0575\u0569\u056b \u0585\u0580\u0565\u0580\u056b\u0576 \u0576\u057e\u056b\u0580\u057e\u0561\u056e \u0583\u0561\u057c\u0561\u057f\u0578\u0576 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0574]</ref><ref>[http://www.archmuseum.am/?p=1814/ \u0531\u057d\u0561\u0576\u0584-\u0531\u0576\u0561\u0576\u0584 \u0583\u0561\u057c\u0561\u057f\u0578\u0576\u0568 \u0587 \u0543\u0561\u0580\u057f\u0561\u0580\u0561\u057a\u0565\u057f\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0561\u0566\u0563\u0561\u0575\u056b\u0576 \u0569\u0561\u0576\u0563\u0561\u0580\u0561\u0576-\u056b\u0576\u057d\u057f\u056b\u057f\u0578\u0582\u057f\u0568]</ref>\n*[[2011]]-[[2012]] worked as a Theatre Expert in the \u201cArmenian-Turkish Reconciliation Project\u201d in [[Mu\u015f]] ([[Turkey]]) \u0587 [[Gyumri]] ([[Armenia]]).\n\n\nTsolak MLKE-Galstyan is a member of [https://www.ietm.org/ IETM- International network for contemporary performing arts]. <ref>[https://www.ietm.org/en/satellite-cairo-2018/session/whos-disabled/ Satellite Cairo-2018-Session: Who's Disabled]</ref> <ref>[http://www.panarmenian.net/m/arm/news/67652/ \u00ab\u0544\u056b\u0570\u0580\u00bb \u0569\u0561\u057f\u0580\u0578\u0576\u0568 \u0574\u0561\u057d\u0576\u0561\u056f\u0581\u0565\u0581 IETM-\u056b \u0569\u057e\u0578\u057e 30-\u0580\u0564 \u0561\u0574\u0565\u0576\u0561\u0574\u0575\u0561 \u0570\u0561\u0574\u0561\u056a\u0578\u0572\u0578\u057e\u056b\u0576]</ref>\n\n== Performances ==\nTsolak MLKE-Galstyan is the choreographer of  21 performances of  [[Mihr (theatre)|MIHR Contemporary Dance Company]] and Art. Director of more than 70 shows.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m60aJiLJUWg/ CV - \u0544\u053b\u0540\u0550 \u0539\u0531\u054f\u0550\u0548\u0546` \u054a\u0561\u0580\u056b \u0578\u0582\u056a\u0576 \u0578\u0582 \u056f\u056b\u0580\u0584\u0568]</ref>\n \n*2018 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-song-of-a-refugee-2018//\"The Song of a Refugee\"] (\u054fite-specific Contemporary Dance Performance) \n*2017 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/we/\"We\"] (Inclusive Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2015 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/lavash/\"Lavash\"] (Physical Performance. Contemporary Dance)\n*2015 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/names/\"Names\"] (Emotional Dance. Contemporary Dance)\n*2014 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-fly/\"The Fly\"] (\u054fite-specific Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2014 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/no-more-lies-2014/\"No More Lies\"] (\u054fite-specific Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2013 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-sound-of-loneliness-2013/\"The Sound of Loneliness\"] (Music of Movement)\n*2012 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/soldiers-2012/\"Soldiers\"] (Contemporary Dance)\n*2012 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/conversation-of-thoughts-2012/\"Conversation of Thoughts\"] (Open-air Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2011 ''Plays about Death'' [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-murderer-2011/\"The Murderer\"], [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-mortally-ill-2011/\"The Mortally Ill\"], [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-suicidal-2011/\"The Suicidal\"] (Contemporary Dance)\n*2010 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/dreams-in-dreams-2010/\"Dreams in Dreams\"] (Contemporary Dance)\n*2010 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/black-castle-2010/\"Black Castle\"] (Open-air Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2009 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/komitas-10-commandments-2009/\"Komitas 10 Commandments\"] (Emotional Dance. Contemporary Dance) \n*2008 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/sasna-tsrer-sanasar-and-baghdasar-2008/\"Sasna Tsrer. Sanasar and Baghdasar\"] (Multimedia, Ethno-Modern Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2007 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/the-colors-2007/\"The Colors\"] (Action-Painting Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2006 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/am-i-crazy-2006/\"Am I Crazy?\"] (Drama Dance. Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2005 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/roots-2005/\"Roots\"] (Open-air Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2004 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/creation-2004/\"Creation\"] (Phosphoric Movement Contemporary Dance Performance)\n*2003 [https://mihrtheatre.com/project/which-is-our-guilt-god-2003/\"Which is our Guilt, God?\"] (Open-air Contemporary Dance Performance)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*\u0412\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0415\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 (2013). ''\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0446 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430. \u00ab\u0411\u0410\u041b\u0415\u0422\u00bb. ''{{ISBN|978-5-901818-12-1}}\n*Next Stage Europe 3 (2017). ''Contemporary Theatrical Texts by  Armenian, Georgian, Azerbaijani and Russian playwrights. Graf & Graf.''\n\n==External links==\n*[http://mihrtheatre.com/ Official Website] \n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B5N59ES_Fn8/ Where does the dance begin?: Tsolak Mlke-Galstyan at TEDxYerevan]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OEHE5y7HBd0/ \u053b\u0574 \u0563\u0580\u0561\u0564\u0561\u0580\u0561\u0576\u0568. \u0551\u0578\u056c\u0561\u056f \u0544\u056c\u0584\u0565-\u0533\u0561\u056c\u057d\u057f\u0575\u0561\u0576]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:MLKE-Galstyan, Tsolak}}\n[[Category:Contemporary dance choreographers]]\n[[Category:Armenian directors]]\n[[Category:Armenian dancers]]\n[[Category:Armenian painters]]\n[[Category:Armenian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Choreographers]]\n[[Category:Dance in Armenia]]\n[[Category:Contemporary dance compa